<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Contest-Animals,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Cited By Animal Control When She Submits Entry of Dead
Animals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman tried to submit as a contest entry
a display of nine dead animals wired to a board in the shape of a
radio station's call letters.
   Elaine Hougland, 20, of Seymour, Ind., was cited by the Jefferson
County Animal Control and Protection Agency.
   Agency Director Eric Blow said Ms. Hougland claimed the four
squirrels, two opossums, two house cats and a chicken were ``road
kills,'' picked up after they'd been struck by cars.
   Blow and his deputies said, however, the animals did not appear
to have been run over.
   The contest was sponsored by station WDJX, which had invited
listeners to bring entries displaying its call letters in unusual or
creative ways.
</TEXT>
