<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Soviet 3rdLd-Writethru a0614 12-18 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Soviet, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0614,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diverging Interests, Security Concerns Block Asian Detente</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 21 grafs to UPDATE with Shevardnadze comments,
Japanese officials' comments re Gorbachev; Pickup 25th pvs,
`Shevardnadze is...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze arrived
Sunday on the first stop of an Asian tour, which officials ope will
pave the way for a Japan-Soviet summit and ease tensions over a
longstanding border dispute.
   ``Under a new atmosphere, Japan-Soviet relations are able to
enter a new track of normal development,'' Shevardnadze told
reporters after his Aeroflot jet landed at Tokyo's Haneda
International Airport. ``This is something we have been waiting
for.''
   Substantial political dialogue between the two Asian powers is
overdue, he said, adding, ``We're trying to decide what to do.''
   Shevardnadze's visit to Japan, the Philippines and communist ally
North Korea comes as Moscow courts capitalist Asian nations with
requests for economic cooperation and promises of military cutbacks
in the region.
   In the latest overture, contained in a U.N. address Dec. 7,
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev pledged to ``reduce
significantly our armed forces in the Asian part of the country.''
   Asian debtor nations, including the Philippines, welcomed
Gorbachev's suggestion of a 100-year moratorium on Third World debt.
   But Asian and Soviet officials say Gorbachev's Asian initiatives
since his visit to the Soviet Pacific port of Vladivostok on July
28, 1986, have produced few concrete payoffs.
   Soviet relations with China have improved recently, but relations
with most of the rest of Asia remain stagnant or chilly _ crippling
Moscow's efforts to expand trade and technology exchanges with
industrialized Asia.
   Theoretically, Moscow has much to offer: an enormous potential
market for Asian goods, scientific and technical aid and abundant
natural resources.
   In return, Asia could sell high technology and provide badly
needed foreign investment.
   During his four-day Japan visit, Shevardnadze will meet with
Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno for talks expected to include the
dispute over Soviet-held islands off Japan's northern Hokkaido
province.
   Both Moscow and Tokyo claim the southernmost section of the
Kurile chain, but Soviet troops ousted the 17,000 Japanese residents
at the end of World War II and have occupied the territory since.
   The dispute has been the main obstacle preventing the two nations
from signing a peace treaty to formally end wartime hostilities.
   In downtown Tokyo, authorities tightened security around the
Soviet Embassy where the foreign minister is staying. Busloads of
police were seen on street corners near the walled compound, a
favorite target of right-wing groups demanding return of the islands.
   Japanese officials say they will also renew a 2-year-old
invitation for Gorbachev to visit Japan. Gorbachev's plans for a
Tokyo visit two years ago were postponed.
   ``This time we'll have foreign ministerial sessions,'' Uno told
the Japan Broadcasting Corp., ``but naturally I'd like to see a
(Prime Minister Noboru) Takeshita-Gorbachev summit and I intend to
bring up this subject during this round.''
   Shevardnadze is expected to discuss Japanese investment in
Siberia during his visit. Gorbachev has remarked that his plans to
develop the vast Soviet Far East will require substantial input from
Japan.
   This Soviet need for advanced technology may have given Japan
leverage to negotiate over the disputed islands, said Ichiro
Suetsugu, who heads the private Council on National Security
Problems.
   Japanese business and government officials say a major diplomatic
breakthrough would help but not guarantee expanded economic ties.
   They complain Moscow lacks the hard currency needed to pay for
high-technology imports, joint ventures are unprofitable and Japan
doesn't need more Soviet timber or oil.
   After his visit to Tokyo, Shevardnadze will travel to the
Philippines and North Korea. His trip takes place as Soviet-backed
Vietnam is withdrawing more troops from Cambodia, helping to ease
tensions in the region.
   Shevardnadze is traveling to Manila at his own initiative in what
Philippine officials call a ``get to know you'' visit. He will be
the highest-ranking Soviet official to visit the former U.S. colony
since President Corazon Aquino assumed office in February 1986.
   Officials in Australia and New Zealand, the biggest powers in the
South Pacific, have said Soviet economic penetration of the region
could lead to a dangerous Kremlin military presence.
</TEXT>
