<DOCNO> AP881218-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 0522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Vanuatu     12-18 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Vanuatu,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Reported Arrested As Power Struggle Deepens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who was sworn in as the new
prime minister of this island nation Sunday was arrested hours later
by security forces loyal to his ousted predecessor, radio reports
said.
   Barak Sope's arrest fueled the dispute over who is in power in
Vanuatu, a country of 130,000 people about 1,200 miles northeast of
Brisbane, Australia.
   Sope was sworn in Sunday by President George Sokomanu, who on
Friday announced he was dissolving Parliament and dismissing Prime
Minister Walter Lini. Sope and Lini, who took office in 1980, have
been locked in a power struggle for a year.
   Lini said he would not yield power, and many in Parliament
questioned whether Sokomanu's actions were constitutional.
   Radio reports in Sydney said that in addition to Sope, pro-Lini
troops arrested a Cabinet minister whom Lini fired earlier this year
and his chauffeur and secretary.
   The reports quoted Sokomanu as saying the troops ``were in full
combat gear. Some were carrying machine guns, others had rifles.''
   Earlier Sunday, Sokomanu appointed a five-member interim
government which he said would rule Vanuatu until national elections
in February.
   Lini became prime minister in 1980 when Vanuatu, formerly the
Anglo-French New Hebrides, gained independence.
   Sokomanu's decision to dismiss him and dissolve parliament
followed by-elections last week that gave Lini's governing Vanu'aku
party two-thirds control of the 46-seat Parliament.
   The opposition boycotted the vote, and Sokomanu said the present
Parliament therefore was unconstitutional because no opposition
candidates were put up for election.
   Sope told reporters he might seek military help from Australia or
other Pacific states if Vanuatu's security forces refuse to support
him.
   Australia has said it will continue to recognize Lini as the
legitimate prime minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
