<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WinterSolstice     12-18 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Winter Solstice,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Pauses, Then Turns North Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The winter solstice is nearly upon us again, an
event long celebrated as marking the triumph of the unconquered sun
but today more often dreaded as the start of winter.
   Overshadowed in this season of religious holidays and the
approaching new year, the solstice was once the most popular of
pagan celebrations.
   It marks the lowest point of the year for the sun's apparent
travel, occurring at 10:28 a.m. EST, on Dec. 21, according to the
U.S. Naval Observatory.
   After the solstice, the sun begins spreading its warming rays
farther and farther north until reaching a zenith at the summer
solstice in June.
   Primitive societies, fearing the sun's departure, often developed
complex folk tales about the change in seasons, and learned to
celebrate the winter solstice as a time of rebirth foreshadowing the
coming return of summer.
   Indeed, sociologists note that many aspects of this event were
incorporated into Christian festivities marking the birth of Jesus,
which is now a major event of this season.
   To residents of ancient Rome the season was known as Saturnalia
and was celebrated with raucous merrymaking. That has since been
generally toned down, or at least postponed until New Year's eve.
   The Germanic tradition called Yule remains popular in many areas,
however. That feast incorporated burning of a special yule log,
decorating with plants such as holly, ivy and mistletoe which were
thought magical, and drinking wassail toasts.
   Gail Cleere of the Naval Observatory reports that great bonfires
were lit atop hills in hopes of encouraging the return of the sun.
   Today, most calendars list this date as the start of winter
despite the fact that there are no ``official'' definitions of the
seasons.
   Meteorologists, for example, consider winter to begin Dec. 1. In
medieval times Nov. 23 was considered that season's beginning, and
most people simply judge winter's arrival by how cold they feel when
they go outdoors.
   At any rate, the coming months mark the coldest time of the year
thanks to the fact that, although the sunlight is gradually
increasing, it takes some time to overcome the cooling that has been
underway during autumn when the light was on the decline.
   That thermal lag notwithstanding, spring will come, to be
welcomed by those following medieval tradition on Feb. 22, by
meteorologists on March 1, by calendar makers on March 20 and by
most folks on the first balmy day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
