<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrideAbducted     12-18 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bride Abducted,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bride Abducted En Route to Church But Thief Returns Her On Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man hijacked a limousine carrying a bride-to-be
and her bridesmaids, but he dropped the screaming women off at the
church just in time for the ceremony and then sped off.
   The wedding came off more or less as planned, and sympathetic
police officers drove the bride and groom to their reception.
   Although the hijacker and the limousine were not recovered,
police may have a good shot at finding him: one of the bridesmaids
snapped a farewell photo of the abductor.
   The saga began when Sharon McEachern, two of her bridesmaids, the
maid of honor and a friend from Florida arrived early for the 11:15
a.m. Saturday wedding at St. Mark's Church in Boston. The priest,
the Rev. William Devine, suggested they take a quick drive in the
limousine.
   The bride was nervous, and her throat was dry, so she asked the
limousine's chauffeur, William Spitz, to pull over at a convenience
store to buy a soda. Spitz obliged.
   While he was in the store, a man hopped in the limousine, said he
needed the car, and drove away with the bride and her friends inside
screaming and begging to be let out.
   ``I was in the front seat with him,'' said Lisa Ferguson, the
friend from Florida, who described the man as in his 30s, blond and
wearing a red ski hat. ``He just said, `Excuse me girls, but I need
this car.' He kept apologizing, but he said he had to get away from
the police.''
   The man also took $20 and a personal check for $25 from the women.
   The women managed to persuade their captor to drop them at the
church. As a parting shot, Ferguson yelled, ``Smile,'' and snapped
his picture as she fled the limousine.
   McEachern and Timothy Moccia were married, but since there was no
limousine to escort them to the reception, Boston police volunteered
their cruisers.
   ``The bandit got them to the church on time, but the police got
them to the reception on time,'' Detective Walter Fahey said proudly.
   At the reception, the groom's brother offered a toast: ``I hope
your married life is a lot smoother than the ride to get here.''
   The couple will spend their honeymoon in the Bahamas.
</TEXT>
