<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TimberSales     12-18 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Sales,615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Service: Overall, Timber Sales Make Money For Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of timber from government-owned forests
make money for the government overall although most forests lose
money, according to a new Forest Service study.
   The study, required by Congress because of years of disputes over
whether the sales in effect amount to government subsidies for
timber companies, was immediately attacked by a chief critic of the
sales who said the study would have found overall losses if proper
accounting practices were used.
   The current report covers the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, 1987,
and will be used to compile an updated version for the following
year and then a formal report to Congress for the current year.
   In a preface of the report addressed to ``Dear National Forest
User,'' Forest Service chief Dale Robertson said receipts from
timber sales in fiscal 1987 exceeded costs by $540 million.
   Roughly half that sum has to be returned to state and local
governments, leaving the federal government $267 million ahead from
the sales, the service said.
   The Wilderness Society, however, said in a statement the new
system ``greatly understates the costs of selling timber,'' thus
overstating any profits. The society said it believed proper
accounting would show a fiscal 1987 loss of $223 million and average
annual losses of $406 million from 1982 though 1987.
   The Forest Service study showed a pattern of frequent moderate
losses offset by large gains, notably from the productive forests of
the Pacific Northwest.
   The Forest Service region of Oregon and Washington accounted for
$460 million of the receipts over expenditures, 85 percent of the
total gain of $540 million. Put another way, Washington-Oregon had
$2.64 in revenue for every dollar of expense, while the system as a
whole had $1.76.
   Past studies have shown similar dominance by the Pacific
Northwest. A 1984 study by the General Accounting Office, covering a
period when timber prices were lower, said the Pacific Northwest
gains outweighed losses in all the remaining regions of the system.
   In the study, gains were reported in three other regions _
Arizona and New Mexico, $1.52 in revenue per dollar of cost;
California, $2.07 per dollar; and the Southeast, a region that
includes Texas and Oklahoma, $1.62.
   All other regions lost money: Montana, North Dakota and northern
Idaho, 88 cents of revenue per dollar expense; Rocky Mountains
(eastern and central Wyoming, Colorado, South Dakota, Nebraska and
Kansas), 56 cents; western Wyoming, southern Idaho, Utah and Nevada,
57 cents; Minnesota, Iowa, Missouri and states to the east north of
the Ohio and Potomac rivers, including West Virginia, 87 cents;
Alaska, 25 cents.
   The harvest of 12.7 billion board feet of timber generated more
than 139,000 jobs in affected communities and $3.83 billion in
income, including rents and returns on investments, the service said.
   The timber sales also produce other benefits that cannot be
assigned monetary values, including ``sustained yields of various
wildlife habitat to support a variety of species, reduced forest
protection costs, reduced probability of catastrophic fires,
increased visual diversity and watershed improvements.''
   The Wilderness Society statement said 76 of 120 forests lost
money, in part because the service assigns too little cost to
road-building.
   ``One bookkeeping trick that the Forest Service uses is to
amortize the costs of roads and bridges over the entire interval
between timber harvests. For example, in the Rocky Mountains road
costs are spread out over a period ranging from 122 to 331 years.''
   This means only a tiny fraction of road-building costs are
charged against timber receipts in a given year, while private
companies would recover those costs in 20 to 30 years.
</TEXT>
