<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HolidayGiving Bjt   12-18 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holiday Giving, Bjt,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donations Brisk In Some Cities, Lagging In Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA BARNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to holiday giving, every town has its Santas and
Scrooges, but some communities seem to have an abundance of one or
the other this year.
   With a week to go before Christmas, charities are reporting mixed
results. Donations are up or holding their own in some places and
down in others, according to checks with the Salvation Army, the
United Way, Catholic Charities, the Red Cross, food banks and other
groups.
   Efforts to aid the victims of the earthquake in Soviet Armenia
appear to be having an impact on domestic giving in some cities, the
charities say.
   There seems to be no pattern: collections are up in big cities
like New York and Chicago, but down in Los Angeles. In the Midwest,
Kansas City and St. Louis reported healthy donations, while Oklahoma
City was having a more difficult time.
   Nor was a strong economy necessarily a sign of success: Donations
were up in Boston, but those in neighboring Rhode Island were
struggling to stay even.
   Local factors account for some of these differences, such as
shopping malls that ban Salvation Army kettles. Others have to do
with the weather, competition among charities, the local economy, a
shortage of bell ringers and a shift of donations earlier this year
into campaign coffers.
   Charity officials in Boston credit their success to a more
sophisticated approach to hat-passing as well as seasonal good will.
   ``There seemed a tendency to give more and we also broadened our
base by going to more people. A lot of people don't give because
they haven't been asked,'' said Wallinda Hudson, spokeswoman for the
United Way of Massachusetts Bay, which raised $48.7 million in
pledges for its 1988 campaign, up 10 percent over 1987.
   It's a different story in Arizona, where charities say an
economic downturn is behind a decline in giving. Paul Curnow, the
Salvation Army's development director in Phoenix, cites a 12 percent
to 25 percent drop.
   The story is much the same in Detroit and Newark, N.J. Giving is
down by at least $60,000 from last year for the Salvation Army in
Detroit. Thelma Cloude, director of the Greater Newark Social
Services and Correction Bureau, said, ``This year, with the
upsurgence of the working poor, those who used to help us now need
help themselves.''
   Other areas are suffering from a dearth of volunteer or low-paid
donation-collectors _ ironically a result of a strengthening economy
that has more people working, charity officials say.
   In Rhode Island, which has an unemployment rate of 3 percent, the
Salvation Army Corps of Providence is hurriedly trying to recruit
volunteers, said Capt. John E. Wettlaufer. ``For a full-timer, we
have one woman that works every day and she's 86 years old, God
bless her,'' he said. College students have pitched in on weekends.
   In Georgia, with more volunteer bell ringers than ever, Salvation
Army officials said kettle donations are up by 15 percent. However,
mail donations are off by 6 percent.
   For fund-raisers in Southern California, the campaign drain has
been the problem.
   ``The fact of the matter is that we usually suffer every four
years when there's an election,' said Russell Prince, the Salvation
Army development director in Southern California, where donations
are running 15 percent behind last year.
   In Richmond, Va., Salvation Army officials blame a drop at the
kettles on cold weather and shopping mall managers who barred the
bell-ringers.
   Americans' response to the Armenian earthquake was viewed as
having an impact on domestic giving in some cities, such as Detroit.
   ``People that give to that (Armenia) seem to dig a little deeper.
It hasn't affected our income,'' said Don Payton, director of
development for the Salvation Army in Denver, who estimated that
donations were running 6 percent to 8 percent above 1987.
   The Red Cross' Southeast Michigan chapter faces a bittersweet
situation, spokesman Mark Cornillie said.
   ``A lot of people are converting their gifts to Armenia, and in
that case, we absorb the cost of handling that money. So not only
are we losing money that people traditionally give to us at this
time of year, but we're losing it in the administration end,'' he
said.
   Meanwhile, the need for assistance keeps growing, spokesmen say.
A program to provide toys, coats and food for needy families in the
Newark, N.J., area had 1,600 families request aid this year, double
last year's total, said Ms. Cloude.
   While the amount of goods donated to the South Central
Pennsylvania Foodbank in suburban Harrisburg is about the same as
last year, the demand for food from its 300 participating agencies
has increased, said Assistant Director Jodie Morris.
   But officials retain faith in Americans' willingness to respond
to need. ``When people see people in need, and they see an
opportunity to help, they will,'' said national Red Cross
spokeswoman Barbara Lohman.
</TEXT>
