<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Ethics Bjt   12-18 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Ethics, Bjt,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Plans Own Ethics Bill in Wake of Troubled Reagan
Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush, entering the White House
on the heels of an administration bedeviled by ethics accusations
against senior personnel, plans to move quickly on his own ethics
bill early next year, aides say.
   Although Bush supported President Reagan's pocket veto of ethics
legislation that Congress passed this year, he intends to put forth
a package that will include some of the same elements, said the
president-elect's legal counsel, Boyden Gray.
   ``We've already started very preliminarily to put our thoughts
together on it. The anticipation is that we will have a bill late
this winter, early spring,'' Gray said in an interview.
   During the campaign, Bush walked a careful line to avoid direct
criticism of former Attorney General Edwin Meese III, who was under
investigation by an independent counsel, while trying to signal that
his own administration would hew to high ethical standards.
   Independent Counsel James McKay later declined to prosecute
Meese, but concluded that the former attorney general probably broke
federal conflict-of-interest laws twice by handling matters
affecting the telecommunications industry at the time he held
telephone stock.
   In a news conference last week, Bush promised to carry through on
his campaign pledge, saying, ``I will have ethics legislation. I
spoke about it in the campaign, my commitment to high ethical
standards and I will have proposed legislation go up very, very
early.''
   Gray said drafting has not begun. He has not specifically
discussed proposed ethics legislation with the Justice Department
yet, but said his staff has held preliminary talks with
representatives from the Office of Government Ethics.
   Gray said Bush intends to include some planks that were not in
the legislation Reagan vetoed last month, including applying the
same restrictions to members of Congress as those that apply to
executive branch employees who leave government.
   The congressional legislation only banned lobbying activity for
one year for people who left Congress, but imposed a lifetime ban in
some circumstances for executive branch employees. Bush has
supported a one-year ban on congressional lobbying by former members
of Congress.
   The complaint of the Reagan administration, in which Bush serves
as vice president, was that the 1988 congressional bill imposed far
more restrictive rules on executive branch employees.
   In vetoing the bill, Reagan said he considered it ``excessive and
discriminatory,'' and said it would hamper good people from entering
the government.
   Administration officials criticized the bill because it forbade
former executive branch employees not only from lobbying their
former division but also aiding or advising clients on dealings with
that division.
   That aiding and advising clause, which was a lifetime ban, will
be left on the cutting room floor of the Bush proposal, Gray said.
   More than 100 officials in the Reagan administration have been
accused of wrongdoing, and at least six, including former Deputy
Chief of Staff Michael K. Deaver and Lyn Nofziger, Reagan's former
political director, have been convicted.
   Bush has promised to set up a White House ethics office, with a
permanent ethics office in each government department and agency.
   During his campaign, he pledged greater discretion for
prosecutors in pursuing civil and criminal sanctions, depending on
the gravity of the case, against those who violate
conflict-of-interest standards.
   He also said all blind trusts for government officials should be
managed by institutions rather than individuals.
   Gray said Bush also would consider the White House as one entity
for purposes of post-employment lobbying restrictions rather than
precluding people from lobbying only the section of the executive
branch where they worked.
   ``The compartmentalization of the executive office of the
president, I think, is something the vice president thinks is
somewhat artificial and ought to go,'' Gray said, ``because they
interact on such a daily basis.''
   In other words, a person would be barred from lobbying not only
the part of the White House where he or she worked, such as the
Office of Management and Budget, National Security Council or office
of the vice president, but would be restricted in contacts from all
White House sections.
   Gray said he also will try to push Bush's proposal for some
regulation on ``influence that people may wield before they leave
office,'' that could affect their post-government careers.
   ``The revolving door tends to focus almost exclusively on what
people can do after they leave,'' he said.
   But people can still make decisions involving companies that
might hire them after they leave government. Such post-government
employment would not necessarily involve lobbying their former
government agency, but in these cases, ``they've already done it,''
Gray said.
   ``I think it's a problem in the Pentagon. I think its a problem
in every department to a greater or lesser degree _ people
feathering their nest,'' he said.
   Gray said he has not yet sat down with Justice Department or
Office of Government Ethics officials to determine how regulations
to deal with that aspect might be worked out.
</TEXT>
