<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Soviets     12-18 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Soviets,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Confident Soviets Ready To Drop Najib</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla spokesman said
Sunday he was confident Moscow is ready to abandon its communist
protege in Kabul, President Najib.
   ``I believe the Russians know their puppet regime can't stay,''
Burhanuddin Rabbani, chairman of the seven-party Afghan guerrilla
alliance, told a news conference.
   ``They (the Soviets) don't want the present regime to be there,''
he said, referring to Najib and his ruling Marxist People's
Democratic Party of Afghansitan.
   Rabbani led a guerrilla delegation at high-level talks with
Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov Dec. 3-5 in the Saudi
Arabian resort city of Taif. He said that at that meeting, Vorontsov
told guerrillas: ``We want a new system, a new situation.''
   Vorontsov and the guerrillas are expected to return to the
negotiating table in Islamabad before the end of the month, rebel
and Pakistani sources said.
   On Saturday, a low-level Soviet delegation met with Afghan
guerrillas, but the guerrillas said the talks concerned only
prisoner exchanges and ended without agreement.
   The Soviet Union intervened in Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up the
Marxist government. Last April, the Kremlin agreed to pull half of
its estimated 100,000 troops out by Aug. 15 and the rest by next
Feb. 15.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas have been waging a war against the
Kabul government for the past 10 years. Their headquarters is in
Pakistan's frontier city of Peshawar.
   Rabbani said the guerrillas have demanded removal of the ruling
communists, reparation money, an end to Moscow's weapons aid to
Kabul and recognition of ``a government framed by the (rebels).''
   If the Soviets prove they share a commitment to peace, Rabbani
said, then the guerrillas will guarantee Red Army troops safe
passage out of the country.
   ``The mujahedeen will not create any obstacles on their way out''
provided the Soviets give them advance knowledge of departing
troops, Rabbani said.
   The seven-party alliance has scheduled a meeting Monday to review
the Taif talks and hammer out a ``broad-based council'' that could
step into the breach in Kabul should the ruling communists abandon
the capital, Rabbani said.
   The council, he said, would include representation from different
segments of Afghan society with the exception of the Kabul
communists. However, the alliance has not agreed whether it would be
established through elections or by appointment, he said.
</TEXT>
