<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumorBackfires     12-18 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humor Backfires,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Employee Fired for Posting Funny Signs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLAY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city employee trying to lighten up City Hall
found out that her boss didn't appreciate her sense of humor.
   Water system clerk Betty Murphy was fired after she placed a sign
asking residents if they wanted to ``speak to the man in charge or
to the woman who knows what's going on.''
   Mayor Sharooz Jamie said he discharged Murphy, who is also the
elected city recorder, because he didn't think funny signs belonged
on the walls of City Hall.
   Murphy said Jamie never complained about the signs until recently.
   ``People bring them in and I put them up,'' she said last week.
``I've done it ever since I was elected'' last year.
   Murphy said she continued to put up notes on the front door of
City Hall after she lost her job Dec. 6 and was locked out of the
building. She said Jamie tore down one note saying she would be back
for her belongings, leading her to put up another note that said,
``I shall return.''
   ``City Hall is not a joking place,'' Jamie said. ``She must think
she's (General Douglas) MacArthur.''
   The recorder, who supervises city finances, has no office in City
Hall.
   Jamie and Murphy have often disagreed on city business, including
Murphy's initiative to remove a speed bump from a back street while
Jamie was out of town. She said the noise from cars was bothering an
elderly man who lived on the hill above it.
   Murphy has filed a lawsuit in Clay County Circuit Court to
determine whether she can be fired as water clerk.
   Jamie said Murphy would continue to serve as recorder. ``I don't
have any problem with working with her,'' Jamie said.
   Clay, which has a population of about 500, is about 30 miles
northeast of Charleston.
</TEXT>
