<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     12-18 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Soldiers Kill Black Policemen In Bungled Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African soldiers hiding
out in what they believed was a guerrilla safe house shot and killed
two black policemen and an alleged informer who approached the
building, police said Sunday.
   The victims also believed the building was a base for the
outlawed African National Congress and were arriving to investigate,
police said.
   The ambush in the Soweto township occurred on Wednesday but was
not reported by police or the army until Sunday newspapers described
it.
   Police refused to say if weapons were found in the house or
identify the owner. The Sunday Times quoted a neighbor, Richard
Gondolwane, as saying: ``I didn't know my neighbors well as they had
only lived there for a short time.''
   After being tipped off by an unidentified informant, soldiers hid
inside the house Wednesday, according to the reports.
   About the same time, four policemen, three black and one white,
were told by the alleged informer that the house was occupied by ANC
members, police said. They went to investigate and were shot as they
approached the house at night, according to police headquarters.
   The Sunday Times reported that they victims were fired upon after
they broke down the door of the darkened home and burst inside.
   The soldiers, believing they were firing at ANC members, killed
two black policemen and the alleged informer and injured the third
black policeman. The white officer was not hurt, police said.
   The policy of having white South African soldiers on duty in the
black townships is a controversial one.
   Anti-apartheid organizations have made removal of the soldiers a
major demand, and the situation has been an issue in trials of draft
resisters who say it is inappropriate for white soldiers to be
called to perform military service in neighborhoods where their
fellow black citizens live.
   It was not clear whether the soldiers involved in the shooting
were career officers or young draftees performing their mandatory
two years of service.
   ``If the soldiers were national servicemen, it was extremely
reckless to use young men who obviously have not had the training
for action of this sort,'' said Helen Suzman, a Parliament member
from the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party.
   ``This is another good reason for not sending the army into the
townships and for only using men who are properly trained.''
   Under apartheid, blacks have no vote in national affairs and have
separate districts and schools from whites, who control the economy.
</TEXT>
