<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Protest     12-18 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Protest,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibetans Reportedly Stage Anti-Chinese Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60 Tibetan students demonstrated Sunday
against China's policies in Tibet, where Chinese forces recently
killed at least one monk, an American journalist said.
   The journalist said he was the only Western reporter who
witnessed the demonstration and that police stopped him from talking
with students and shoved him into a police van.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said in a report late Sunday that
more than 70 Tibetan students had been persuaded not to stage the
demonstration at Tiananmen Square, the political center of Beijing.
   It said the students, from the Central Institute for
Nationalities, had not applied for permission to stage a
demonstration and were taken back to the institute by bus.
   Seth Faison, of the South China Morning Post in Hong Kong, said
five Chinese police officers pulled him away from the protesters,
picked him up and pushed him into the police vehicle.
   Faison, 29, of Brooklyn, N.Y., said he was questioned for two
hours and released.
   He was told he violated three city regulations: trespassing on a
public lawn, disturbing the flow of traffic and failing to follow
police instructions. Police told him he would not be charged with
the violations, Faison said.
   Faison said he saw about 60 people marching in western Beijing
shortly before noon. The marchers told him they were Tibetan
students.
   ``They are killing our people, they are killing our people,''
Faison quoted the marchers as saying.
   Pro-independence activists clashed with Chinese security forces
in Tibet's capital, Lhasa, on Dec. 10. Official Chinese reports said
one monk was killed and 13 people were injured when security forces
shot at the activists.
   Western witnesses said they saw two bodies, including a small
child, and that Tibetans told them seven people were killed.
   Faison said the marchers told him they had walked down
Changanjie, Beijing's main street, past Tiananmen Square and
Zhongnanhai, a walled compound housing offices and homes of some of
the country's highest-ranking leaders.
   Faison said he did not know whether any were arrested because he
was removed from the scene quickly. The Xinhua report did not
mention arrests.
   Tibetan activists seeking an end to 38 years of Chinese Communist
rule in Tibet and the return of the Dalai Lama have demonstrated
repeatedly over the past 14 months in Lhasa. A small group of
Tibetans also marched in Beijing late last fall.
   At least 38 people were killed in violent clashes with police on
Oct. 1, 1987 and in March in Lhasa, Western travelers said.
   The Dalai Lama, whom Tibetan Buddhists believe is the
reincarnation of Tibet's protector god, led Tibet's civil
administration before Communist Chinese troops entered in 1950. He
fled to India in 1959 during an abortive anti-Chinese uprising.
</TEXT>
