<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites Sub a0649 12-18 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, Sub, a0649,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to CORRECT spelling of Verkhoyansk throughout
and eliminate incorrect reference to Yakutia as a Soviet republic.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although this town on the
Canadian border bills itself as the ``Nation's Icebox,'' it can't
truly compete for the world title.
   So, says Mayor Jack Murray, if you can't beat 'em, join 'em.
   Murray hopes to set up a sister-city relationship with the
Siberian village of Verkhoyansk, which, according to a history of
the region, has recorded temperatures as low as 90 degrees below
zero.
   ``I just thought it would be good public relations and some good
publicity to go with things we're doing here,'' said Murray, whose
city is trying to further promote itself as a cold-weather testing
site for products ranging from clothing to car batteries.
   That's even though its record low is a mere 46 degrees below zero.
   International Falls is trying to make contact with Verkhoyansk
through Paul Mala, a specialist in cold-weather research from
Anchorage, Alaska, who is attending a conference in Leningrad.
   While there, Mala plans to meet representatives from the Siberian
region where Verkhoyansk is located, and give them a packet from the
International Falls Chamber of Commerce.
   The plan is for Verkhoyansk's residents to somehow get the
documentation of their sister-city relationship to Anadyr, a
Siberian city on the Pacific Coast. There it will be picked up by
arctic explorer Paul Schurke, who plans a 1,200-mile dog-sled
journey March 1 that will end in Alaska.
   The documents, Schurke said Friday, would then be carried by car
to International Falls.
</TEXT>
