<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1407EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-QuakeRelief     12-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake Relief,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team Of Rescue Workers Returns From Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAMIL HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Americans that
spent a week in Soviet Armenia in the aftermath of a major
earthquake there returned home Sunday, speaking solemnly of the
devastation and admirably of the survivors.
   ``It's hard to put into words the absolute, total devastation of
the area,'' said Michael Tamillow, a member of the group, which
included 10 firefighters from Virginia, eight from Florida, eight
dogs trained to search for bodies, their 12 handlers and five
doctors.
   Tamillow said he was amazed at the resilience of the Armenian
people and credited Soviet troops with helping rescue workers from
the United States and other countries.
   ``The true heroes are the Armenian people,'' said Tamillow, a
firefighter from Fairfax, Va.
   Tamillow said subfreezing weather tested the mettle of the relief
workers.
   ``We were literally camping out over there in 20-degree
weather,'' he said. ``We were running low on water and we had no
firewood.''
   Tamillow said Soviet troops would visit the American base camp
nightly and bring firewood. Soviets and Americans often exchanged
stories and souvenirs, he said. ``We would give them candy and they
would give us things,'' he said.
   Tamillow was part of a team that assembled Dec. 9, two days after
the earthquake, at the request of the Office of Foreign Assistance,
an arm of the Agency for International Development.
   One of the returning doctors, Claude Cadoux of Chevy Chase, Md.,
said the physicians set up a makeshift hospital at an airport where
there also was a base camp for relief workers.
   The facility was designed to support the rescue operation but
also treated survivors of the earthquake, which killed an estimated
55,000 people and left an estimated 500,000 homeless.
   ``Once the people learned we were there they came to us for care
because of the overburden of facilities in the region,'' Cadoux said.
   Dr. Vartkes Najarian, an Armenian-American from Glendale, Calif.,
said residents of the earthquake-ravaged area were grateful for the
assistance of the dogs in searching through the rubble for survivors
and bodies.
   ``They started kissing and hugging the dogs and then they went
into their homes to bring food,'' Najarian said.
   About 30 Armenian-Americans from the Washington area were at the
base when the team returned and presented its members with gifts.
Family members and co-workers also were on hand for the arrival.
   Earlier Sunday, an Aeroflot flight carrying 20 kidney dialysis
machines and other medical supplies left Andrews for the Soviet
Union, according to the Armenian Relief Society, a group based in
Watertown, Mass. A separate plane carrying a medical team and
supplies left Newark, N.J., for the Soviet Union, the group said.
</TEXT>
