<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0663 12-18 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Garcia Submits Resignation as Head of His Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with party official saying Garcia
will remain in post. Pick up 4th graf pvs, ``Critics accuse ...''
DELETES outdated 9th graf, edits to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia offered his resignation
as top leader of the governing party after he received a bitter
reception at his party's national convention, officials said Sunday.
   Garcia, Peru's president since July 1985, submitted a letter
placing his post as president of the Aprista Party at the
disposition of the party, Aprista said in a statement.
   Party official Ferdando Leon de Vivero issued a statement Sunday
afternoon saying the party would keep Garcia at its helm and that
party directors backed Garcia fully.
   In Garcia's letter, published in Lima newspapers Sunday, he said:
``I am no longer a man of triumph. I am an Aprista upon whom all the
insults fall. Without desiring it, others at my side can be hurt.''
   Critics accuse Garcia of implementing policies that have brought
on Peru's worst economic crisis this century and have failed to stop
the leftist Shining Path movement, whose eight-year guerrilla war
has claimed more than 12,000 lives.
   The offer to resign referred only to Garcia's Aprista post and
not his position as the nation's president.
   The president's opening address to the convention in Lima Friday
night was marred by a shouting match between the 39-year-old
politician and many of the hundreds of party members in the
auditorium.
   It was the most strident opposition from within his party that
Garcia has faced since emerging as a leader of the center-left party
early in the decade.
   The opposition ``offends the nationalistic and popular image of
our party ... it serves to divides us,'' Garcia said in the
resignation document, which was delivered late Saturday to the 16th
National Congress of the Aprista Party.
   Garcia's reputation _ both within his party and outside _ has
plummeted in the face of the economic crisis.
   Political analysts say the economic woes also have severely
strained the country's fragile democracy. Rumors of a pending
military coup have surfaced repeatedly in recent months.
   Since Garcia imposed the harshest austerity program in Peru's
history in early September, some members of his own party have
demanded he resign as the nation's president. Others have called for
presidential elections to be stepped up by six months.
   Garcia's approval rating among Peru's 21 million people has
plunged from 96 percent during his first months in office _ he was
called the ``president of hope'' by many party members _ to 16
percent in late October, according to the respected polling firm
Apoyo.
   Novelist Mario Vargas Llosa, named a candidate for president
Friday by the center-right coalition Democratic Front, has emerged
as one of Garcia's harshest critics.
   Most independent economists agree that Peru's current recession
is caused by runaway inflation expected to hit 1,800 percent this
year and by uncontrolled government spending.
   The next general elections are set for 1990, when Garcia's
five-year term ends.
</TEXT>
