<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DartmouthReview     12-18 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dartmouth Review,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Editors Of Conservative Newspaper Face Hearing On Bias
Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE MAGRUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dartmouth College and students the Ivy
League school punished for harassing a black professor go to court
Monday in a struggle between the administration and a conservative
off-campus newspaper.
   The students, former editors of the weekly Dartmouth Review, will
ask a judge to find enough merit to their claims that they are
victims of reverse discrimination to lift their suspensions
provisionally.
   John Sutter, 22, and Christopher Baldwin, 21, both white, were
suspended in March by a campuswide disciplinary panel. The panel
found the two guilty of disorderly conduct for failing to leave
Professor William Cole's classroom after being asked.
   The paper had called Cole's music class ``one of Dartmouth's most
academically deficient'' in an article that drew charges of racism
against the newspaper.
   A third student received a shorter suspension and a fourth got
probation for the February classroom clash with Cole.
   The Review's defenders say that had the students been black and
Cole white, the discipline would have been far less severe.
   Sutter, Baldwin, the third suspended student and the Review
charged in federal and state lawsuits that they were targeted for
being outspoken about their conservative views, which include
opposition to women's studies courses and affirmative action at
Dartmouth.
   The third student is not part of the hearing because he returned
to class this fall, said college spokesman Alex Huppe. The fourth
student did not join the lawsuits.
   ``The students were disciplined to such a severe degree that even
the college has no plausible explanation other than as a punishment
for the statements and articles in the newspaper, and that's a
violation of their freedom of expression,'' said Arthur Ruegger, a
lawyer representing the students.
   To Dartmouth, the issues involved are authority and autonomy.
   ``From the college's point of view, this is a private
discip| matter, and we're taking that extremely seriously,''
Huppe said Friday. ``We're obviously defending the college's
disciplinary procedures.''
   The hearing in Grafton County Superior Court is on bids by
Baldwin, of Hinsdale, Ill., and Sutter, of St. Louis, for a
preliminary injunction. If they win, they will return to Dartmouth
in January rather than in September, when their 18-month suspensions
expire, Huppe said.
   Though the hearing won't decide the core issues of the state
lawsuit, it will be an important first reading, Ruegger said.
   The Review's supporters include such prominent conservatives as
William F. Buckley Jr. and Sens. William Armstrong, R-Colo., and
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H. Both senators attended a Washington news
conference in July to announce the lawsuits.
   Huppe said no First Amendment issues are raised directly in the
state case, which he said is based on contract law.
   But Ruegger said freedom of expression will be addressed because
it is guaranteed to students in Dartmouth's student handbook.
   Baldwin, who has worked at Buckley's National Review since being
suspended, was one of 12 students, mostly Review staffers, who
conducted a nighttime sledgehammer attack on shanties erected on the
college green in 1986 to symbolize the poverty of South African
blacks.
   The raid, coming hours after a service marking the birthday of
slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., triggered a
semester of turmoil.
   In March, shortly after the college rejected appeals by Baldwin
and the other disciplined students, Dartmouth President James
Freedman called a special faculty meeting to denounce the Review for
``poisoning the intellectual environment of our campus'' and
threatening its ``moral endowment.''
   Freedman dismissed Review staffers as ``ideological provocateurs
posing as journalists.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
