<1ST_LINE>u i AM-TribalWedding     12-18 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tribal Wedding,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedding Unites Rival Zulu and Xhosa Tribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISHO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prince and princess of rival
tribes were married in a Christian ceremony Sunday that followed
three days of traditional festivities, including the ritual
slaughter of an ox.
   The marriage joined the royal households of South Africa's two
largest tribes, the Zulu and the Xhosa, and was noteworthy in a
nation where some whites believe blacks are incapable of cooperating
across tribal lines.
   Princess Nomusa Jeannett Bhekuzulu _ 25, the sister of the Zulu
king _ married Prince Maxhoba Sandile _ 40, the paramount-chief
designate of the Rarabes tribe of the Xhosas _ in the Bisho, the
capital of Ciskei.
   Ciskei is a Xhosa homeland that was designated as independent by
South Africa but that is not recognized by other nations.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha, Ciskei President Lennox
Sebe and Zulu King Goodwill Zwelethini attended the wedding. The
Zulus have refused the government's efforts to make their territory
a separate nation.
   On Friday, Xhosa and Zulu women wearing beaded skirts, necklaces
and anklets danced and chanted in the mud and blood around a speared
ox.
   Tradition dictates that each time the ox is speared and does not
fall, the bridegroom's family must forfeit another goat to the
bride's household. So the Xhosa women waved straw switches at the
ox, urging it to die, while the Zulus held a mirror to its face so
it could see its fate and rise to its feet.
   The bridegroom and his men, wearing beads and wrapped in
blankets, entered the royal corral near the Ndakana Great Place,
where pieces of abdominal tissue of the sacrificial beast were
sprinkled with salt and buried.
   The bride and her bridesmaids, covered in blankets to keep their
faces hidden, entered the stockade. The bride plunged a spear into
the mud at the entrance, committing herself to the future of her
husband's home.
   On Sunday, about 4,000 people gathered in Ciskei's Independence
Stadium amid tight security to watch the Western-style, Christian
wedding ceremony performed by a minister of the Order of Ethiopia.
   Botha arrived on a Ciskei Defense Force helicopter and presented
the couple with a loaf of bread baked by his wife. He said they
should eat it together and remain together, calling the marriage ``a
sign of the future for southern Africa'' when all its inhabitants
could come together in peace and harmony.
   Local newspapers said the marriage was the first time royal
members of the historically antagonistic tribes had married.
   The Zulus and the Xhosas are the two largest tribes in South
Africa, each with more than 6 million, and each alone outnumbering
the whites who rule the country. The wedding could be significant
politically because of the belief by many Afrikaners, the Dutch
descendants who control the government, that South African blacks
cannot cooperate across tribal lines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
