<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate Says Will Continue Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential candidate Manuel J.
Clouthier entered the fourth day of a hunger strike Sunday and said
he will continue the fast until ``Mexico has a fair, honest
electoral law.''
   Clouthier was the candidate of the conservative National Action
Party in Jully 6 elections won by President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has
not lost a major election in its 59 years of rule.
   Both Clouthier and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who ran for a
left-of-center coalition and came in second in official results,
maintain there was widespead fraud in the election and vote count.
   ``Carlos Salinas de Gortari has formal but not moral authority to
govern the country,'' Clouthier told a news conference Saturday at
the tent where he is holding the hunger strike. ``What is needed
here is legitimacy.''
   He said he would continue the strike until ``Mexico has a fair,
honest electoral law that does not make one party privileged.''
   National Action said before Salinas' inauguration Dec. 1 that he
could acquire legitimacy by governing well and insuring the fairness
of elections. It also protested the results of state elections Dec.
4 in four states.
