<2ND_LINE>AM-Honest Boys,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honest Boys Rewarded By Strangers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strangers passed the hat and raised nearly $100 for
two boys who returned a lost wallet containing $2,000 and received
only a $1 reward from the wallet's owner.
   ``Boy, did that guy make me mad,'' said John Bartolo, 35, a city
housing authority worker who raised the money Saturday after
learning of the small reward, which was reported in a newspaper. ``I
did it to make these kids feel better. I wanted to put the screws to
Ebenezer Scrooge.''
   The boys, Tommy Martel, 9, and Scott Senesi, 7, found the wallet
Thursday near their home in suburban Somerville, The Boston Herald
reported Sunday. The newspaper did not identify the wallet's owner.
   Bartolo said he enlisted some friends who went through several
bars, restaurants and a market to solicit donations for a more
fitting reward.
   Peggy Martel, Tommy's mother, said she was touched by what
Bartolo did.
   ``After talking with my husband and Scott's parents, we decided
to give the money to the kids because it will show them if they do a
good deed, they will be rewarded,'' she said.
   The boys said they found the brown wallet lying in the street and
took it immediately to Tommy's mother.
   ``I didn't even count the money, but I could see there were new
$100 bills,'' Mrs. Martel said.
   She tried to call the wallet's owner at his Medford home, then
found him at his job in Somerville.
   ``He looked everything over and said he had just come from the
bank with $2,000 and somehow dropped his wallet on the street. Then
he pulled out a dollar and handed it over for the kids,'' she said.
   ``I said, `You don't have to do that.' A nice thank you actually
would have been better than a dollar.
   ``But I don't want to put this man down. We don't know what his
circumstances are. The money wasn't ours to begin with, so giving it
back was the only thing to do.''
  
</TEXT>
