<HEAD>Three Former DEA Agents Investigated In Heroin Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Asian heroin valued at $7.5 million apparently
disappeared from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration regional
office, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   More than five pounds of heroin vanished in separate incidents in
1984 and 1985 after DEA agents seized the drugs as evidence, the Los
Angeles Times reported, citing unnamed sources close to a corruption
investigation.
   The probe has focused on the alleged corruption of former DEA
agents John Anthony Jackson, Darnell Garcia and Wayne Countryman,
who were indicted Dec. 7 on conspiracy and tax charges.
   Federal investigators, according to the newspaper, have linked
Jackson to the suspected theft of 2{ pounds of heroin from a DEA
vault in 1984.
   Jackson also participated in a 1985 heroin investigation in which
DEA undercover agents bought 15 pounds of heroin, but booked only 12
pounds as evidence, according to the same unnamed sources.
   Jackson, 39, who is being held without bail, declined a Times
request for an interview, the newspaper said. Attorneys representing
the three agents also declined to comment.
   Prosecutors have said the three DEA agents were tied to cocaine
trafficking and may have alerted Los Angeles drug kingpins to
federal investigations.
   However, the only charges filed so far against the former agents
involve an alleged plot to defraud the Internal Revenue Service and
making false statements on currency reports. The former agents
allegedly laundered more than $608,000 through Swiss bank accounts.
   Countryman, 45, was released after posting $120,000 bail; Garcia,
42, is a fugitive.
