<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Protest     12-18 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Protest,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Demand Closing Of Plant Where 1987 Accident Occurred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIBLIS, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 people demonstrated
outside the Biblis nuclear power plant Sunday to demand the closure
of the facility, where a recently disclosed malfunction took place
in 1987.
   About 170 groups participated in the demonstration, including the
environmentalist Greens Party and the West German Federation for
Environmental Citizens' Initiatives.
   Earlier in the day, police dragged 24 demonstrators out of the
plant's ``information center,'' which they had occupied overnight.
The two dozen protesters all were released but face possible charges
of disturbing the peace.
   During Sunday's demonstration, speakers repeated assertions that
a serious nuclear accident nearly developed at the Biblis plant, 30
miles south of Frankfurt, one year ago.
   Pressure for closing the Biblis plant erupted earlier this month
after a U.S. technical newsletter disclosed that on Dec. 16-17,
1987, operators there allowed a malfunctioning cooling system valve
to go uncorrected for 15 hours. A small amount of radioactive steam
escaped into the atmosphere during the incident.
   The company that runs the plant, Rheinisch-Westfaelisches
Elektrizitaetwerk, denies trying to conceal information about the
incident, and said it caused no damage to the public.
   Environmentalists charge that the accident could have led to a
nuclear core meltdown, but West German atomic officials say the
plant is outfitted with emergency systems that would have prevented
such an occurrence.
</TEXT>
