<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Quake 1stLd-Writethru   12-18 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0652,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans to Help Rebuild Armenia, No More Survivors Reported Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd pvs, `But Armenians..., to UPDATE
with reports on weather, Politburo commission. Pick up 3rd pvs,
`Pravda, the... Minor editing to trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB1, MOSB3, MOSB5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. seismologists flew to the Soviet
Union Sunday to help rebuild cities shattered by Armenia's
earthquake, Tass said, as the Soviets turned their efforts from the
rescue of survivors to reconstruction.
   But Armenians ``whose senses have been dulled by grief'' continue
to hope more survivors can be found under collapsed homes and
apartment buildings, state-run Radio Moscow said 11 days after the
earthquake that killed an estimated 55,000 people.
   The evening TV news program ``Vremya'' said snow was forecast
Monday for Armenia, with temperatures as low as 9 degrees at night.
That would hamper relief workers trying to dig under the rubble and
pose more hardships for thousands of homeless now living under tents
and out of doors.
   ```We must hurry!' These words are now in the souls and on the
lips of thousands of people who are helping liquidate the
consequences of the tragedy,'' Tass said in a report on Sunday's
meeting of a special Politburo commission overseeing the relief
effort.
   The commission, which visited the stricken city of Spitak, said
the evacuation of children, women and the elderly from the disaster
zone was nearing completion, and that in two or three days, ``only
those who participate in rehabilitation work would remain.''
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, reported that in the first 10
days following the Dec. 7 quake, 15,252 people had been dug out
alive from the ruins of Armenian cities and villages, where an
estimated 500,000 people were left homeless.
   But judging from official media reports, attempts by Soviet and
foreign rescue teams to locate additional survivors in the shambles
of Leninakan, Spitak and other northwest Armenian cities crumbled by
the quake were becoming futile.
   Only one survivor was rescued in the 24-hour period ending
Saturday night, the Tass news agency said. During the same period,
89 bodies were extricated from the ruins.
   There were no reports Sunday of any more survivors.
   ``The first, most acute phase of the rescue effort is coming to
an end,'' Radio Moscow said. ``Preparations have started for
restoring the industries and housing.''
   Dutch television journalist Alexander Munninghoff, who returned
to Moscow Sunday from Spitak, said all foreign relief workers had
been asked to leave the city by Tuesday, apparently because the
search was ending.
   No official announcement has been made of an end to the search, a
potentially explosive issue in Armenia, where some people have sat
in front of bulldozers to prevent the clearing of debris until it
can be searched for victims.
   AP photographer Boris Yurchenko, who also was in Spitak, said the
city that was once home to 25,000 people was now nearly deserted,
with a few people searching for relatives remaining behind and
taking shelter in tin garages left standing by the quake.
   An estimated 15,000 people were killed in Spitak, and many
decomposing bodies still lie buried in ruined buildings.
   ``The smell is becoming more and more pronounced every day,''
Yurchenko said. ``The first sign of the terrible threat of an
epidemic _ dead dogs and swarming rats _ are forcing rescue teams to
hurry, since no leveling of the town can be done with corpses still
remaining in their stone graves.''
   Tass said 16 American seismologists were flying to the Soviet
Union Sunday, bringing specialists in the construction of
earthquake-resistant buildings and in the organization of rescue and
rebuilding operations.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has criticized the flimsy five-and
nine-story apartment buildings constructed in the 1960s and 1970s
that collapsed during the quake.
   Armenian activists, embittered by Moscow's refusal to grant their
demands in a territorial dispute with neighboring Azerbaijan, have
accused the central government of bungling relief efforts and not
doing enough to warn Armenians of the danger of an impending
earthquake.
   Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, who heads a special Politburo
commission overseeing the relief campaign, expressed frustration
with the ``unwelcome moods'' of some Armenians in comments broadcast
Sunday by Radio Moscow.
   Soviet media continued to report on an official crackdown against
Armenian militants, including members of the Karabakh committee, six
of whose leaders have been arrested.
   The committee has spearheaded the 11-month-old campaign for
annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian district of
Azerbaijan.
   Tass said the Soviet Union has concluded an agreement with the
U.S.-based American Telephone and Telegraph Co. that will allow
Armenians to make collect calls to the United States, where many
have friends and relatives. Usually, Soviets cannot place collect
calls.
   Tass said that since the quake, telephone traffic between Armenia
and the United States has increased eight-fold.
</TEXT>
