<HEAD>Two Israeli-Allied Militiamen Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two militiamen of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army were killed Sunday when a bomb planted by guerrillas
exploded at the militia's radio station, the station said.
   Islamic Resistance, a Lebanese pro-Iranian resistance group,
claimed responsibility for the attack. It said said its guerrillas
infiltrated Israel's self-designated security zone in south Lebanon
and planted three bombs around the premises of the militia's Voice
Of Hope radio station.
   ``Then they fired two rockets at the radio station before
returning safely to base,'' said a spokesman for the group, who
refused to be identified.
   A statement released earlier by Islamic Resistance said the
guerrillas ``blew up'' the radio station, inflicting ``heavy losses
on the (pro-Israeli) agents.''
   The Voice of Hope, in its midday newscast, said the two
militiamen were killed as they were defusing one of the bombs. It
denied the station had been damaged.
   The radio station is located in Marjayoun, the provincial capital
of the security zone which is patrolled by both Israeli troops and
SLA militiamen.
   Israel established the narrow strip just inside Lebanon in 1985
when it withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon following a
three-year occupation. It maintains the six- by 10-mile strip as a
buffer against border guerrilla forays into northern Israel.
