<HEAD>Walesa Convenes Citizen's Committee to Voice Opposition Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, ``On the ...'' to CORRECT that Solidarity
banned in 1982 sted 1981; PICKS up 12th graf pvs, ``In the ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Sunday
convened 128 intellectuals, artists and activists, and they
organized into a permanent citizen's committee that will address
Poland's social and political problems.
   The committee began as an informal council that Walesa has
invited to five meetings since May 1987 to make policy statements on
behalf of the country's opposition movement.
   The new permanent committee is to meet four times a year and
establish 15 commissions that will examine social problems and
suggest solutions, said committee members who gathered Sunday in a
church near the Roman Catholic Episcopate in Warsaw.
   Topics to be dealt include political and economic reform,
education, housing, culture, youth and ecology.
   Among those who are to contribute to the commissions are experts
who have been preparing the planned talks between Walesa supporters
and the government on Poland's future.
   As a condition for holding talks with the government, Solidarity
has asked the government to declare its intent to legalize the trade
union federation, which was banned in 1982.
   Andrzej Wielowieyski, an adviser to Walesa and a spokesman for
the committee, said Sunday that members of the new committee view
the planned talks as only one way to begin a dialogue with the
government. He said the discussions could take place in other forms,
such as through the newly-formed commissions.
   Walesa hinted Thursday in Gdansk that he expected a breakthrough
in the dialogue with authorities, but Sunday's meeting produced no
new signs of such an agreement. However, Walesa confirmed that
low-level contacts between the opposition and authorities have
continued in recent weeks.
   Walesa said he was represented by the Rev. Alojzy Orszulik, an
official of the Roman Catholic Church who has been in touch with
Stanislaw Ciosek, a deputy party Politburo member.
   The forming of the new committee came before a key Communist
Party Central Committee meeting Tuesday and Wednesday in which
officials plan to discuss prospects for speeding up political reform
and democratization.
   On the surface, relations between Walesa and the authorities have
never been so cordial since the government declared martial law and
cracked down on the trade federation in 1981, a year after Walesa
formed Solidarity. Solidarity was outlawed in 1982.
   In the past month, the Solidarity leader has been allowed to
speak in a national TV debate, was permitted on his first foreign
journey in seven years _ to France _ and his statements and
activities have been publicized and even praised in the official
media.
   On Thursday, Walesa said recent remarks by government spokesman
Jerzy Urban have come ``very close'' to Solidarity's demand that the
government express its intent to legalize Solidarity. But Walesa
said the ```i' still has not been dotted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
