<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Police     12-18 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Police,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Officers Defy Government And Elect Union Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers on Sunday defied the
government and went to the polls to elect union representatives for
the first time in the 155-year history of their force.
   Thousands of police officers gathered in central Athens to elect
a 15-member executive committee for the Union of Lower Ranking
Police Officers, the first in Greek police history.
   Despite government objections, the union was set up earlier this
year to represent officers with a rank of sergeant or below. The
union now has 18,000 registered members, said Sgt. Kostas Siggounis,
acting chairman of the union.
   The government, which claims it is unconstitutional for police
officers to form a union, has threatened them with transfers to
remote provincial posts, administrative punishment and dismissal,
union founders say.
   Union elections took place in the provinces last week and all
votes will be counted in Athens on Sunday.
   The Greek police is structured much like an army and is run by
the Ministry of Public Order, which has said that unionization
disrupts the chain of command and ``the police hierarchy's method of
operation.''
   ``They are worried that we will start questioning orders and
upset the hierarchy in the Greek police,'' said Yiannis Kotsis,
another union member.
   The Greek constitution forbids members of the police to go on
strike but ``doesn't say anything about forming a union,'' Kotsis
said. Because of his union activities, the officer has been
transferred from Athens, where he served for 17 years, to the
northern town of Grevena, about 275 miles north of the capital.
   Siggounis and other officers say their aim is to modernize the
force and secure better living and working conditions. A police
officer's starting salary is $394 a month, Siggounis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
