<HEAD>Dallas Museum Gets $20 Million Donation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A philanthropist has donated $20 million to the
Dallas Museum of Art, which will help the museum expand its space by
half, museum and city officials said.
   ``This is a great Christmas present to the museum,'' museum
president Vin Prothro said of the donation by Nancy Hamon, a
longtime supporter of the arts. ``This is a great Christmas present
to the city.
   ``This is something that will take us well into the future,''
Prothro added. ``This is the biggest gift in the history of the
Dallas Museum of Art, by far.''
   Mayor Annette Strauss said that in addition to providing an
impetus for future development in the downtown Arts District, an
expanded museum would have a positive impact on downtown business.
   ``It would bring tourists, and that helps our downtown hotels and
other businesses,'' Mrs. Strauss said.
   The donation is earmarked for a three-story wing that would be
named after Mrs. Hamon and her late husband, Jake. The museum
contains an eclectic collection ranging from South American
primitives to Picassos.
