<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Continues to Bleed, Blood Pressure Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito suffered internal bleeding for the
fourth consecutive day and his blood pressure fell Sunday, the
Imperial Household Agency said.
   The 87-year-old emperor, who has been bedridden since Sept. 19,
is hemorrhaging from the upper intestine, where he underwent a
bypass operation last year.
   Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda told reporters the amount of blood
Hirohito discharged Saturday and Sunday was ``quite small.''
   Maeda said the ailing monarch's systolic blood pressure was 94
over 40 Sunday morning and 90 over 46 in the evening. An average
reading is about 120 over 80.
   Police, meanwhile, reported a fire Sunday at the Musashiryo
imperial mausoleum in Hachioji, near Tokyo, where Hirohito's father,
Emperor Taisho, and mother are buried.
   The fire, believed to be arson, razed trees west of the
mausoleum, said a police officer who requested anonymity. He said
investigators believed the fire was set by radicals opposing the
monarchy.
</TEXT>
