<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-18 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls In California, Nevada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold, moist air produced snow Sunday in the northern mountains of
Southern California and western Nevada, as well as light drizzle in
parts of Southern California and rain showers along the central
California coast.
   Snow fell at a rate of an inch an hour at Reno, Nev., on Sunday
morning. The western valleys of Nevada received 1 to 2 inches of
snow, and the eastern foothills of the Sierra Nevada as well as the
Lake Tahoe area had as much as 8 inches.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Sunday night and Monday for
higher elevations of northern Arizona, where some areas were
expected to receive up to 6 inches of new snow.
   A weather system moving into the northern Rockies was expected to
bring snow in high elevations and freezing rain in the valleys of
western Montana.
   High winds blew along the eastern slopes of the Rockies in
Montana. Winds gusted to as high as 68 mph at Cutbank, Mont.
   Elsewhere, cold, westerly winds blowing over the warm waters of
the Great Lakes produced so-called ``lake-effect'' snow Sunday in
some areas on the lakes' eastern fringes. Parts of western New York
state were expected to receive 3 to 5 inches of new snow.
   Light snow also fell in much of Lower Michigan and eastern parts
of Upper Michigan. Two inches of snow fell at Marquette, Mich., in
the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees at Jackson, Wyo., to 71 at Brownsville, Texas. The low in
the nation Sunday morning was 16 below zero at Jackson.
   The forecast for Monday called for rain showers in New Mexico and
Arizona, with snow in higher elevations; snow in the northern
Rockies and western portions of the northern Plains; rain along the
central Pacific Coast; a mixture of snow showers and rain showers in
western New York state; lake-effect snow in the Upper Peninsula of
Michigan; and light snow in northern Maine.
   High temperatures were forecast to reach only the teens in
northern Maine; the 20s and 30s from the northern Intermountain
region across the northern Rockies, North Dakota, the upper
Mississippi Valley, most of the Great Lakes region, and from the
central Appalachians to the remainder of New England; in the 60s
from Southern California and Arizona across the southern Plains, the
lower Mississippi Valley and the Gulf Coast states to the southern
Atlantic Coast and northern Florida; and the 70s in southern Texas
and southern Florida. The remainder of the nation generally will
have highs in the 40s and 50s.
</TEXT>
