<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Airport-Guns     12-18 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport-Guns,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Hare Police Arrest Man After Discovering Weapons in Suitcase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Filipino native was arrested Sunday at O'Hare
International Airport after a search of his family's
Philippine-bound luggage revealed two automatic weapons, seven
handguns and parts for several more, police said.
   The arrest occurred as the man, identified by police as Lamberto
Camacho, prepared to put his wife and two children on a Northwest
Airlines jet headed for Manila.
   ``We think this guy is a part-time gun-runner,'' said Sgt. John
Fanning of the Chicago Police Department's O'Hare unit. ``He told us
the extra parts were for weapons that already had gone through
previously.''
   Fanning said Camacho, 44, of Defiance, Ohio, works as a lab
technician for General Motors Corp. He was charged with unlawful use
of a weapon and attempting to board an airplane with weapons,
Fanning said.
   Fanning would not say why the man, who did not have a ticket, was
charged rather than the wife and children, who had tickets. The
weapons were found in the family's checked baggag.
   A routine X-ray of the luggage, he said, ``revealed an Uzi
(automatic machine pistol) hidden among the clothes in one suitcase.
A subsequent check of the rest of the luggage turned up a
false-bottomed crate where the second Uzi and three other pieces
were stashed.
   ``We found three more (handguns) in another bag,'' Fanning said.
``Apparently, there's a lot of money to be made running guns into a
place where there's political unrest.''
   Camacho was being interviewed by agents of the FBI, and
investigators from both the Federal Aviation Administration and the
U.S. Customs Service, and may face federal charges in addition to
the state charges already filed, Fanning said.
   He was expected to be transfered to a nearby Chicago police
district lockup later Sunday.
</TEXT>
