<2ND_LINE>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0683,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Promises Close Scrutiny Of PLO</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with 6 grafs new PLO statements; pick up 2nd graf pvs,
While acknowledging xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan administration officials on Sunday vowed
to closely monitor whether the Palestine Liberation Organization
honors its anti-terrorism pledge, even as a top PLO spokesman
signaled intentions to continue military attacks on Israel.
   The administration already is under harsh criticism from Israel
for its first-ever dialogue with the PLO. On Sunday, PLO advisor
Khalid Hassan charged in an interview in Tunis that the United
States is pursuing an ambiguous Middle East policy.
   In addition, Salah Khalaf, second in command to PLO leader Yasser
Arafat in Fatah, the largest PLO group, told an Abu Dhabi news
conference that Arafat's denunciation of terrorism last week ``did
not include military attacks against Israel.''
   ``Our struggle will continue until we raise the Palestinian flag
over Jerusalem,'' he said.
   State Department spokesman Dennis Harter said Sunday he was
unfamiliar with the comments and there would be no immediate comment
from the department.
   Meanwhile, administration officials said Sunday they will be
checking to ensure that Arafat keeps his word.
   While acknowledging that Arafat does not control all Palestinian
factions that may engage in terrorism, Assistant Secretary of State
Richard Murphy said U.S. officials ``have our sources, we have our
means,'' of finding out whether he honors his commitment against
terrorism.
   ``We are going to take these things on a case-by-case basis. The
president has made it plain we can't sustain this dialogue if
terrorism continues,'' Murphy said on the ABC-TV program ``This Week
with David Brinkley.''
   National Security Adviser Colin Powell, appearing on another
Sunday television program, said the United States ``will be watching
their performance on terrorism very, very carefully.''
   ``If we see an act of terrorism and it can be traced back to the
PLO leadership ... then clearly, they will be breaking their word,''
Powell said on NBC-TV's ``Meet The Press.'' ``But of course,
violence is a way of life in the Middle East regrettably. And it
isn't clear that every act of violence or every terrorist incident
can be traced back to the PLO. But it is something we will be
watching very carefully.''
   Murphy, speaking on the ABC program, added:
   ``Terrorism has been renounced in words, now we will see what
happens. What is plain is we are not going to go on words alone.''
   Michael Armacost, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
said the United States expected Arafat not only to speak against
terrorism but to expel from the PLO anyone involved in terrorist
acts and also to distance the organization from any ``elements close
to the PLO'' linked to terrorism.
   ``We're not talking simply about condemning. We're talking about
disassociation and expulsion,'' he said in an interview on CBS-TV's
``Face the Nation.''
   Israeli officials, outraged at President Reagan's reversal of
longstanding U.S. policy against talking to the PLO, showed no signs
Sunday of abandoning their position.
   Benjamin Netanyahu, a member of the Israeli Knesset and former
Israeli ambassador to the United Nations, complained that the United
States did not consult with its ally before making the decision
Wednesday.
   Netanyahu called the move ``a surprise at a very late hour in the
night.''
   He warned that the decision will strain U.S.-Israeli relations
and said the ``complete trust'' that Israel had shared with the
United States has been ``shaken badly.''
   ``I think there are specific consequences. I hope we don't come
to that,'' he said on the ABC program. ``You achieve peace by good
faith negotiations and by keeping your commitments, by keeping your
word. And frankly I think there's been a shakeup in our belief in
America's commitment and its credibility.''
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, speaking on the CBS
program, said Israel was skeptical of Arafat's renunciation of
terrorism and would wait ``a couple of months and see if this is
really going to happen.''
   Peres said it was his position that Israel should negotiate with
``every Palestinian ``who is not engaged in terror ... and who wants
to negotiate a peaceful solution.'' But he added: ``I have my doubts
about Mr. Arafat.''
   Armacost, asked how the United States could justify opening a
dialogue with the PLO while its charter calls for the destruction of
Israel, said Arafat's actions this week superseded that declaration.
   The Israelis contend the PLO is engaging in a rhetorical ruse to
win support for an independent Palestinian state it plans to use as
a base to attack Israel.
   Armacost said any such attempt would ultimately hurt the PLO.
   ``They have indicated publicly that they accept Israel's right to
exist in peace and safety,'' he said. ``And if this is a clever
tactical ruse, not only will the dialogue with us go nowhere, but
there is no prospect of peace and they should have no illusions.''
</TEXT>
