<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece 1stLd-Writethru a0688 12-18 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papandreou's Embattled Administration Wins Parliament Approval Of
Budget</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Parliament approving budget,
ADDS background, EDITS to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Sunday approved the 1989
budget proposed by the embattled socialist government of Premier
Andreas Papandreou, who threatened to resign if the spending plan
did not pass.
   Papandreou termed it a vote of confidence. The vote came four
days after the resignation of his deputy national economy minister,
the seventh Cabinet-level official to step down since a
multimillion-dollar banking and arms scandals surfaced in October.
   With a raise of hands Parliament voted 156 to 140, with two
abstentions by leftist lawmakers, in favor of the record $27.9
billion budget that is projected to run a $9.6 billion deficit.
   The budget plan sparked recent strikes and demonstrations by
educators and other government employees who demanded higher pay
raises to keep up with a 15-percent inflation rate.
   All those voting in favor of the budget were from Papandreou's
governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK. The conservative
New Democracy party along with the Greek Communist Party voted
against the budget, describing it as the ``worst in Greek history.''
   The conservatives and the Communists declined to participate in
the five-day debate in the 300-member single-chamber house.
   Rumors circulated before the crucial vote that several PASOK
deputies were ready to bolt the party and vote against the budget.
But defections never materialized, as the 69-year-old Papandreou
made one of his rare appearances in Parliament to keep his deputies
in line.
   The opposition has repeatedly called for Papandreou to resign
since October when the $300 million scandal rose to the surface,
implicating senior members of his government.
   Papandreou has adamantly refused to step down and said he intends
to remain until his term in office expires in June when general
elections are scheduled. But he told a nationwide television
audience Saturday that he would quit if the budget was not approved.
   ``I want to tell the Greek people that this vote is for me a vote
of confidence,'' Papandreou said.
   Opposition parties say government officials were involved in
illegal deals allegedly set up by banker George Koskotas, who is
accused of influence peddling, embezzlement and fraud.
   The transactions allegedly involved _ directly or indirectly _
the prime minister and members of his party, including Papandreou's
son, George, who is minister of education.
   Last week Deputy Defense Minister Stathis Yiotas quit, saying he
``did not want to be associated with adventurers, swindlers and
embezzlers of public money.''
   He charged the directors of the Greek Arms Industry of paying
commissions of millions of dollars for unfulfilled contracts to arms
dealers hiding behind dummy companies. Koskotas claims to have
documents implicating senior government officials in illegal money
transfers abroad.
   The scandal widened when Greek newspapers and opposition parties
accused officials working for the post office, telephone company and
other public services of receiving interest rates above the legal
limit from the Bank of Crete and pocketing the difference.
   Koskotas, the former chairman of the Bank of Crete, fled Greece
Nov. 6 and has been arrested in the United States. The 34-year-old
banker, who first fled to Brazil and Bermuda, is in a Boston, Mass.,
prison awaiting an extradition hearing.
   Koskotas, who ran a house-painting business in New York from 1974
to 1979, also is charged with attempting to defraud the U.S.
Internal Revenue Service. A hearing is scheduled in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan on Jan. 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
