<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DDT-Checks     12-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DDT-Checks,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 3,000 Will Begin Receiving Checks This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,300 plaintiffs in a 1980
lawsuit over pesticide pollution will begin receiving checks this
week ranging up to $22,500 as their shares of a $15 million
settlement.
   Olin Corp. closed the DDT plant at Redstone Arsenal in Huntsville
some 18 years ago. The 1980 lawsuit filed against Olin by the
federal government grew out of reports of illnesses among residents
living near or fishing from waterways fed by a stream from the plant.
   U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon of Birmingham, who approved the
class-action settlement in 1986, reviewed and approved the
distribution formula late last month.
   All 9,400 claimants were required to submit to blood tests and
complete an extensive questionnaire.
   Of the letters going out beginning Wednesday, about 3,300 will
contain checks ranging from $500 to $22,500; the other 6,100 letters
will inform recipients that their DDT levels were not found to be
elevated, officials said.
   ``The good news will be for those who receive letters saying they
have a normal level of DDT in their body,'' Francis McGovern,
special master of the court-approved settlement plan, said Saturday.
   About one-third of the $15 million settlement went to pay for
legal fees and medical testing, he said.
   According to McGovern, the DDT levels of two residents measured
45 times above normal; each will receive a check for $22,500.
Sixteen people had levels 20 times or more above normal and will
receive checks of $10,000 or higher. The lowest payments, about
$500, will go to some 1,625 plaintiffs whose DDT levels were twice
normal.
</TEXT>
