<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 2042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Peacemaking 1stLd-Writethru a0636h-l 12-18 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Peacemaking, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0999</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Middle East Peacemaking: Partial Successes and Lost Chances</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-11 ``I know...the territory' with 5 grafs to
CORRECT Kissinger quote and move up background on 1967 war. Pickup
12th graf `Until now...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 40 years since Israel became a state,
diplomatic efforts to settle the Arab-Israeli conflict have resulted
in a string of partial successes and lost opportunities.
   Saeb Erakat, a Palestinian political science professor at An
Najah University in the West Bank, said the Middle East impasse has
proved resistant to 77 separate initiatives since 1948.
   Even if current efforts lead to a peace agreement, he said, it
would take a long time to overcome the bitterness.
   ``We should not underestimate the years of violence, hatred and
war. There is a wall higher than the Great Wall of China between us,
and it will not be destroyed by the stroke of a pen,'' Erakat said
in an interview.
   Both the U.S. decision last week to open a dialogue with Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization and new prospects for
Soviet-American cooperation have raised the possibility of a new
initiative.
   The initiative likely would focus on convening a U.N.-sponsored
international peace conference. But prospects are cloudy, because
Israel has rejected such a conference as a biased forum and the PLO
as an unfit partner.
   Analysts such as former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger
believe that even if Palestinians and Israelis could be brought to
the table, the meeting would be pointless without first narrowing
differences on key issues.
   ``I know no Arab state, nor do I see anything in (a) PLO
statement, that would accept even the 1967 borders of Israel,'' he
said on ABC-TV's Nightline on Wednesday, apparently referring to
Israel's borders before the 1967 Middle East war in which Israel
seized Arab territory.
   ``I know no Israeli government that can consider going back
exactly to the 1967 borders,'' he said.
   U.S. peacemaking, up to and including the current administration,
has focused on trying to forge compromise over sovereignty and
territory.
   The U.S. initiatives have tried to get the Arabs to accept
Palestinian autonomy and confederation with Jordan in place of a
fully independent state.
   They have supported Israel's need to keep some of the 2,250
square miles of land captured in the 1967 war _ the West Bank and
the Gaza Strip _ but have proposed international guarantees,
security zones and peacekeeping forces to persuade Israel to give up
most of the territory.
   Until now, they have denied participation of the PLO.
   ``Involving the PLO is the new element,'' said Joseph Kostiner of
Tel Aviv University's Middle East studies center. ``It's a turning
point in the peace process.''
   Peace initiatives have usually been set in motion by outbreaks of
war or an upsurge in violence.
   _The first Arab-Iraeli war in 1948 resulted in U.N.-mediated
``proximity talks'' on the Greek island of Rhodes. Headed by U.N.
envoy Ralph Bunche, diplomats shuttled between hotel rooms because
Arab delegations refused to meet with Israelis.
   Israel eventually signed agreements with Syria, Lebanon, Jordan
and Egypt that fixed cease-fire lines, set up buffer zones and
created armistice commissions.
   _In the wake of the six-day war in 1967, U.N. envoy Gunnar
Jarring of Sweden unsuccessfully sought to promote a land-for-peace
settlement in accordance with U.N. Resolution 242, which has served
as the basis for all future peace efforts.
   The resolution calls for Israel's withdrawal from territory
occupied in 1967 and for the right of all nations in the region to
exist within secure borders.
   _In 1969-70, then-Secretary of State William Rogers presented a
series of plans that halted the Egypt-Israel War of Attrition.
Israel agreed to withdrawal based on Resolution 242 and Egypt agreed
to recognize Israel, but the initiative was aborted by the death of
Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser.
   _The Yom Kippur war in 1973 led to the Geneva peace conference
that December, in which the United States and Soviet Union served as
co-chairmen. The conference was the first to bring Arab states and
Israel together face to face.
   The meeting was adjourned after one day and never reconvened.
Egypt, Jordan and Israel participated, but Syria stayed home and the
PLO was not invited.
   _ In 1974, Israel raised with Kissinger the possibility of a
separation-of-forces agreement that included the return of the West
Bank town of Jericho to Jordan. But the idea was shelved when an
Arab summit ruled that the PLO and not Jordan was responsible for
the occupied land.
   _ In 1977, the Soviet Union and United States issued a rare joint
policy statement recognizing the ``legitimate rights'' of the
Palestinians and offering demilitarized zones, U.N. troops and
guarantees to insure Israel's security after withdrawal.
   Egypt's President Anwar Sadat pre-empted the plan by launching
his own intiative.
   _ The 1978 Camp David Accords served as the basis for the
Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty the following year and but failed to
resolve the Palestinian question. They offered Palestinians limited
self-government for a five-year transition period, after which the
final status of the West Bank and Gaza would be determined.
   _ Saudia Arabia's King Fahd, then crown prince, in 1981 offered a
plan that implicitly recognized Israel's right to live in peace. But
tensions leading up to the Lebanon war undermined the effort.
   _ In September 1982 as Palestinian guerrillas were leaving
Israeli-besieged Beirut, President Reagan urged a plan that ruled
out a Palestinian state but proposed that the West Bank and Gaza
Strip become an autonomous region associated with Jordan.
   U.S. diplomacy subsequently focused on getting Jordan's King
Hussein to stand in for the PLO in peace talks at the head of a
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation. That option was dealt a blow in
July when Hussein announced he was severing ties with the West Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881218-0072 </DOCNO>
