<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Klan-Parade     12-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Klan-Parade,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KKK Wishes for `White Christmas,' But Parade Takes Place Without
Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT DORA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ku Klux Klan littered a parade route
early Sunday with hundreds of cards wishing for a ``white
Christmas,'' but a city crew picked up all the cards before the
event began, police said.
   The holiday parade, which earlier had been postponed when Klan
Imperial Wizard Tony Bastanzio threatened to demand a place in the
lineup, went off without incident.
   The small Christmas cards read: ``Dreaming of a white Christmas,
Merry Christmas, the Ku Klux Klan.''
   Police will try to determine where they were printed and who
ordered them, Chief Bob Roberts said. They were distributed between
midnight and 2 a.m., he said.
   ``They came in like a thief in the night,'' Roberts said.
   The city crew had the cards picked up by 9:30 a.m., well before
the midafternoon parade started. Bastanzio declined to comment
before or after the parade.
   Earlier this month, the Lions Club gave Bastanzio permission to
drive a vehicle carrying robed Klansmen in the parade. But the club,
which has sponsored the annual parade for 17 years, later removed
the KKK from the lineup after Mayor Jeff Book and business leaders
objected.
   More than 50 police officers and sheriff's deputies were at the
parade, Roberts said. Police said they were unaware of any Klansmen
in the area.
   A heavy turnout for the parade represented a refusal to accept
racial prejudice in the central Florida community of 6,000, Roberts
said.
   ``That type of action isn't tolerated in Mount Dora,'' he said.
``Communities in general just aren't going to put up with it.''
</TEXT>
