<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0675 12-18 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze, Uno Begin Foreign Ministerial Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with talks beginning, EDITS to
CONFORM; Pickup 12th graf `The Soviet need...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Ministers Eduard Shevardnadze and Sousuke
Uno began talks Monday that diplomats on both sides hope will help
normalize Soviet-Japanese relations, stalled more than 40 years over
an emotional border dispute.
   The two sides were expected to discuss regional issues, including
the Korean peninsula, Sino-Soviet relations and Kampuchea during
their first session, Foreign Ministry officials said.
   A key issue of their three rounds of talks will be the dispute
over Soviet-held Kurile islands off Japan's northern coast _ the
main obstacle Shevardnadze and Uno must overcome to pave the way for
improved relations between the two Asian powers.
   Shevardnadze, who arrived Sunday from Moscow on the first stop of
a three-nation Asian tour, expressed hopes the territorial dispute
will not further delay improvement in Soviet-Japanese relations.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has expressed interest in
increased economic cooperation and political dialogue with Japan.
But no real progress is likely until Moscow agrees to return the
islands, said diplomats in Tokyo who requested anonymity.
   ``Japan-Soviet political dialogue and mutual understanding is
generally delayed'' by the dispute, Shevardnadze acknowledged after
he arrived at Tokyo's Haneda International Airport.
   ``While there are objective reasons for this, it should be
possible to relax or eliminate the reasons for this delay'' in
improved relations, he added.
   The Soviet envoy, his wife and a 40-member entourage were greeted
at the airport by Uno, Toshiaki Muto, the Japanese ambassador to
Moscow, and Nikolai Soloviev, the Soviet ambassador to Japan.
   Substantial political dialogue between the two countries is
overdue, Shevardnadze said, adding, ``We're trying to decide what to
do.''
   Both Moscow and Tokyo claim the Kuril islands, which since World
War II have been occupied by Soviet troops who had ousted the 17,000
Japanese residents. For decades, the Soviets refused to admit a
territorial issue existed, but officials on both sides have said
they hope to make progress toward a resolution during Shevardnadze's
visit.
   Authorities were concerned about Shevardnadze's safety because of
protests by Japanese right-wing groups demanding return of the
islands. The airport was heavily guarded and in central Tokyo,
authorities increased security around the Soviet Embassy, where the
foreign minister is staying.
   One protester, allegedly a member of a rightist group, was
arrested Sunday for ignoring a police order to stop an
anti-Shevardnadze speech amplified by loudspeakers, police said.
   Shevardnadze's visit comes as Moscow is wooing capitalist Asian
nations with promises of military cutbacks in the region and
requests for foreign investment.
   In his discussions with Japanese officials, Shevardnadze is
expected to bring up economic cooperation, which Gorbachev has said
is needed to develop the Soviet republics in Asia.
   The Soviet need for advanced technology may give Japan leverage
to negotiate the disputed islands, said Ichiro Suetsugu, who heads
the private Council on National Security Problems.
   Trade between the Soviet Union and Japan reached $4.9 billion in
1987, but is expected to climb only slightly this year, to $4.98
billion.
   Japanese businessmen, lured by the huge Soviet market, complain
that the Soviets lack hard currency to pay for imported goods and
that restrictions on selling products in the Soviet Union make joint
ventures unprofitable.
   The Foreign Ministry has said the two nations will issue joint
statements on cultural exchanges and protection of migratory birds
after Shevardnadze's departure Wednesday.
   Japanese officials say they also will renew an invitation for
Gorbachev to visit Japan for a summit. The last Japan-Soviet summit
was in October 1973.
   Shevardnadze is to leave Tokyo on Wednesday for the Philippines
and North Korea.
</TEXT>
