<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Church,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Condemns Political Killing, Forced Resignations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas
on Sunday condemned political assassinations and a new leftist
guerrilla practice of intimidating elected officials into resigning.
   ``Political passions are building and respect for the sovereign
will of the people expressed at the polls is respected less,'' he
said during his weekly homily.
   Rivera Damas said an investigation by the church Legal Aid office
found local authorities who are members of the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance on Tuesday killed Francisco Eduardo Bonilla, a
member of the Christian Democratic Party, in Soyapango, four miles
east of San Salvador.
   Bonilla worked with the Central Elections Council in registering
voters.
   ``Testimony gathered by Legal Aid office holds the mayor and city
police of Soyapango responsible, which if confirmed would be
serious,'' Rivera Damas said.
   The mayor, Jorge Corena, is a member of the Republican
Nationalist Alliance, known by its Spanish acronym Arena.
   The archbishop also condemned recent actions by the leftist
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN, the umbrella
group of five guerrilla groups fighting for nine years to overthrow
the U.S.-backed government.
   ``Equally worrisome is the new practice of the FMLN of forcing
elected officials to resign their posts,'' he said. ``Information
from this week tells of three mayors who could not resist guerrilla
threats and announced their resignations.''
   Since May, when new mayors took office, the group has killed
eight mayors it accused of taking part in government
counterinsurgency efforts.
   Arena is currently considered the front-runner against the
governing Christian Democrats in the Salvadoran presidential
elections scheduled for March 19.
