<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WorldDebt     12-18 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Debt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Payments by Debtor Countries Rise to $43 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outflows of money leaving 17 heavily indebted
Third World countries -- from Argentina to Nigeria to the
Philippines -- are due to reach $31.1 billion this year, the World
Bank estimates in a study released Sunday.
   Last year's figure was $21.8 billion, almost one-third lower.
From all Third World debtors the net outflow was $43 billion, up
from $38.1 billion.
   The money was largely payments on debt. It went to commercial
banks and governments in the United States and other industrial
countries, and to intergovernment lenders like the World Bank itself.
   The bank is owned by 151 governments, with the United States
holding the largest number of shares.
   In the past, money tended to flow the other way: out of rich
countries in the form of loans and investments to develop the poor
ones. That tradition was still working as late as 1982 when the big
debtors took in $3.7 billion more than they paid out, according to
the bank's figures.
   The bank issued a statement Sunday emphasizing that loss of funds
by debtor countries hits their people in future generations too.
   ``Although both incomes and consumption have fallen -- incomes in
most highly indebted countries are lower today than a decade ago --
the adjustment burden has fallen mainly on investment,'' it said.
The drop of investment means fewer schools and roads and jobs in the
future.
   Stanley Fischer, vice president and top economist at the World
Bank, said its annual report on debt carried two messages:
   ``The first is that despite remarkably rapid growth in the
industrialized world in 1988, growth in the debtor nations has not
resumed. The second message is that the debt strategy is entering a
new phase, in which debt reduction is playing an increasingly
important role.''
   The report raised the bank's estimate of Third World debt to
$1.32 trillion at the end of this year. The total is expected to
drop to $1.3 trillion in 1989. It said debt has been growing more
slowly in terms of the dollar because of changes in currency values,
some agreements to reduce debt, and the continued reluctance of
commercial banks to make new loans.
   Fischer said governments are rethinking the debt problem. But he
said the idea of a new international body to buy up commercial debt
at a discount is ``just talk.'' He explained that governments in
creditor countries dislike the idea because it could look like
bailing out the commercial banks.
   The idea was urged by Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev in his
speech to the United Nations earlier this month. The trade law
signed by President Reagan last August instructs the secretary of
the Treasury to start negotiations on a new international body, but
adds that he need not if he thinks the move would drive down the
value of the loans.
   Loans of a dozen major debtor countries are selling now at an
average of 40 cents on the dollar, according to the Shearson Lehman
Hutton Developing Country Debt Index.
   The World Bank suggested that commercial banks should do more to
share the benefit of these discounts with the debtor countries.
Debtor governments have already bought back some of their loans for
cash, or allowed creditors to use them for buying up shares in
debtor country industries.
   Governments of the creditor countries were urged to harmonize
their tax systems and regulations to encourge banks to lend more,
and in some cases to guarantee the loans. Those governments should
also encourage imports from the debtors while debtor governments
should change their policies to encourage loans and investments, it
added.
   New figures released by the bank show that in 1980, the share of
the average Argentine in the national income was $1,990, while last
year that share was down to 1,630 of those 1980 dollars. In Mexico
the drop was from $2,690 to $2,290.
   In African countries south of the Sahara, average incomes dropped
5.2 percent in 1987, the bank reported. Though the debts of many
African countries are small, they make a heavier burden than in some
Latin American countries because Africans are fewer and poorer.
   Their average income was down from $570 dollars in 1980 to 440 of
those dollars last year.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari announced on Friday that he
would try to borrow another $6 billion for Mexico in the coming
year. That would be less than about $9 billion the country is due to
pay out as interest and repayments on its present debt of $102
billion.
   Salinas and other leaders of Latin America debtor countries are
expected to make a bid soon to negotiate a cut in the total debt and
the payments on it. Salinas said Mexico would only service its own
debt if payments are compatible with the country's growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
