<2ND_LINE>AM-Sex Abuse,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic School Worker Charged with Sexual Abusing Male Students</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A worker at a Roman Catholic high school has
been charged with sexual abusing male students at the school, paying
one student for sex and secretly videotaping others running naked in
the building's basement.
   Robert E. Cushing, 36, was arrested Friday and charged with six
counts of third-degree sexual abuse, one count of prostitution and
one count of solicitation.
   According to an affidavit, four male students at Dubuque Wahlert
High School said they had engaged in sex with Cushing. The worker
admitted paying one student for sex several times earlier this year,
the affidavit alleges.
   Cushing was released Saturday on a $10,000 bond. A preliminary
hearing was set for Dec. 30.
   ``It was a total shock to us,'' said the school's principal, Don
Miller.
   Although there was no evidence any students were forced to have
sex, ``in my mind, these students are victims,'' Miller said. ``They
were victimized by someone in authority over them.''
   Officials suspended Cushing from his position in charge of
audio-visual equipment after learning of the police investigation
Dec. 8. He had been employed at the co-educational school for 16
years.
   Assistant Police Chief Terry Lambert said that male students ran
naked in electrical and heating tunnels in the school's basement as
part of an initiation rite to a technical drawing seminar supervised
by Cushing.
   A 14-year-old freshman said Cushing told him he had videotaped
the seminar students with hidden cameras ``so they wouldn't tell,''
according to court papers. Lambert estimated the initiation rite had
been going on ``for the last six or seven years.''
   School administrators have called in mental health experts to
counsel the students in Cushing's group.
   ``Just because we're a community of believers doesn't mean we're
a community of saints,'' Miller said.
</TEXT>
