<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Rig-Ordeal     12-18 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rig-Ordeal,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew Tells of High Spirits Despite 22 Hours on Life Raft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a capsized U.S. oil rig
returned to this Canadian city Sunday, telling tales of singing,
joking and fantasizing about ordering pizza during their 22 hours
stranded in an enclosed life raft.
   ``I know I was saying my own special little prayers for
everybody,'' said 27-year-old Lynn Christian, one of two women on
the Rowan Gorilla I oil rig. ``It was scary.''
   The 27-member crew was forced into the raft three days earlier,
when a tow line broke and their rig foundered in the stormy Atlantic
Ocean about 1,200 miles east of New York. Their glass fiber life
capsule, about the size of a van, was battered by 40-foot-high waves.
   The crew was picked up Friday when the storm eased and the Smit
London, the tug that was towing the rig across the Atlantic to the
North Sea, could finally send out boats.
   During its ordeal the crew sang an old folk tune called
``Farewell to Nova Scotia'' about a sailor wondering whether he will
ever see home again. The crewmembers included 25 Canadians _ 24 of
them from Nova Scotia _ an American, and a Dutchman. The American's
name was not immediately available.
   Darrell Smith, a burly 32-year-old crane operator from Yarmouth,
Nova Scotia, recalled the almost-constant sound of patrol planes
above them _ a comforting reminder they weren't alone. They could
exchange messages via a two-way radio on the raft.
   Ms. Christian said the airplanes spawned a joke about calling out
for pizza.
   ``We were thinking about it,'' she said with a laugh. ``The
planes were going over and we were thinking about ordering one.''
   A company official said the crewmembers were all in good health
on their return.
   ``Some of them didn't even want to go to the hospital,'' said
Bill Hedrick, a spokesman for the Rowan Companies of Houston, owners
of the rig. ``They're all smiles; they look great.''
   The U.S. Coast Guard and the U.S. National Safety Transportation
Board are launching inquiries. The rig was registered in the United
States and inspected by Americans.
</TEXT>
