<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethr a0639 12-18 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethr, a0639,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voting Begins After Violence-Wracked Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with voting beginning, comment
from prime minister. Pickup 11th graf `Tamil guerrillas...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lankans voted for a new president
Monday under tight security after a blood-soaked campaign that left
hundreds dead and normal life in tatters.
   Ethnic extremists of the People's Liberation Front have vowed to
disrupt the elections and have threatened to kill anyone who voted.
   A big question mark was how many of this tropical island's 9.3
million eligible voters would ignore the threats and go to the polls.
   On the eve of the balloting, the government decreed that people
who intimidated others to prevent them from voting could face the
death penalty.
   Troops and police took up positions throughout the island to
ensure calm balloting.
   Polls opened under blue skies and balmy weather at 7:00 a.m.
(8:30 p.m. EST Sunday) and were to close at 4 p.m. (5:30 a.m. EST
Monday). Significant returns were not expected until Tuesday.
   Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa was the candidate of the
ruling United National Party and mentor of President Junius R.
Jayewardene, who is barred by the constitution from seeking a third
term.
   Former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike of the Sri Lanka
Freedom Party was the main opposition candidate. Ossie
Abeygoonesekera also was running as the head of a coalition of four
small leftist parties.
   ``This is a battle between the ballot and the bullet,'' Premadasa
said after casting his vote at the Colombo Municipal Council
Reception Hall. ``The bullet must not win.''
   He predicted victory but said the margin would depend on the
turnout.
   The election was held amid mounting bloodshed caused by ethnic
strife.
   Final days of the campaign were marked by waves of killings,
abductions and attacks on political rallies that disrupted normal
life once famed as a tourist haven.
   On the final weekend before the vote, at least 25 people were
killed, including six who died when gunment burst into the home of a
prominent opposition politician.
   The People's Liberation Front, which is threatening to kill
voters, is a shadowy group of extremists from the majority Buddhist
Sinhalese community upset by government concessions to minority
Hindu Tamils.
   Tamil guerrillas fighting for an independent state in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka also called for a boycott.
   Shops in Colombo that normally would be open for Christmas and
New Year shopping were shuttered Sunday and traffic was light.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that despite
heightened security, Sinhalese extremists in the south killed four
soldiers during the weekend, blocked roads by chopping down trees
and knocked down electricity poles.
   Local police blamed the People's Liberation Front for Sunday's
attack on a political meeting at the home of Neville Fernando in
Panadura, nine miles south of Colombo.
   Fernando, a Sinhalese, used to be a member of Jayewardene's party
but he left it to work for Mrs. Bandaranaike's party.
   Fernando was not hurt in the attack, which left six people dead
and six critically wounded, Panadura police said.
   In a communique, the government said ``any person (who) by words,
whether written or spoken, or by signs or by any conduct compels,
induces or incites any other person to refrain from voting at the
presidential elections . . . Shall be punishable with death or
imprisonment for a period of not less than 10 years.''
   It also said security forces were instructed to use ``maximum
force where necessary'' to enforce the decree.
   The People's Liberation Front is viewed as the biggest threat to
the election. It vowed to kill anyone who supported the government
after Jayewardene signed an Indian-brokered accord granting some
autonomy to the Tamils.
   The front also claims the government is incapable of conducting
fair elections, and it has attacked all parties participating in the
election.
   The government blames the front for the deaths of more than 650
people, mostly Sinhalese who supported the government, since the
accord was signed July 29, 1987.
   The Tamil insurrection has claimed at least 8,500 lives since
1983 when militants from the ethnic minority started attacking
government troops and massacring Sinhalese civilians.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's population. All three
presidential candidates are Sinhalese.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent.
   The fighting is no longer a clearly defined conflict between
Sinhalese and Tamils.
   Sinhalese are killing fellow Sinhalese, and rival Tamil factions
clash with each other and with Indian peacekeeping forces trying to
disarm them.
</TEXT>
