<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HotelFire 5thLd-Writethru a0713 12-18 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0713,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead, Nine Injured In Residential Hotel Blaze</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire chief saying discarded match
apparently began fire; quotes from residents, other detail. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through a residential hotel
Sunday, killing one person, injuring nine and forcing the evacuation
of 100 residents, authorities said. Two people were still
unaccounted for at midevening.
   The blaze in the four-story Morningside Hotel apparently began on
the third floor about 9:40 a.m. and quickly spread. The downtown
hotel has 105 rooms, housing transients and some long-term residents.
   Smoke poured from the rear of the L-shaped, brick building, which
also contains a music store and karate school. The building was
largely gutted and a wall collapsed.
   ``I didn't even have time to grab my boots, and my boots were
right there by the door,'' said Helena M.B. TeleRado, 59, a
hairdresser who has lived in the hotel for 10 years.
   Fire Chief Luther Taylor said the fire apparently started when a
match was discarded improperly.
   Robert Ziker, the owner of the 64-year-old hotel, said resident
Julius Wood died in his fourth-floor apartment. Police said he was
49 years old.
   At midevening, Mayor Joe Kernan said that two people were still
unaccounted-for, but that authorities did not think they were
victims.
   ``We are hopeful and feel pretty good that there is no one left
in the building, but we can't say that with certainty until the
search is completed,'' said Kernan.
   Taylor said the building was destroyed but had no estimate of the
loss. The 60 firefighters and 15 pieces of equipment called to the
scene concentrated on rescuing residents before fighting the fire,
he said.
   At one time, the estimate of the number of unaaccounted-for was
as high as 16. ``Throughout the morning, we had people call in or
come down to the command post'' at a nearby church, said Lt. Richard
Kilgore, public information officer for the police department.
   Officials at Memorial Hospital and St. Joseph Medical Center
reported treating nine people. Four residents were admitted, one of
them in critical condition and another in serious condition,
officials at the two hospitals said. The other five people were
treated and released.
   Lester White, 46, a disabled former truck driver, said he watched
third-floor windows shatter from the heat after he fled the
building, and saw a man waiting for rescue while flames leaped from
the apartment next door. White escaped without his possessions but
was unharmed. ``That's the only thing I'm happy about,'' he said.
   ``The desk clerk came by the door and knocked and said,
`Fire!','' said Jeannie Skelton, 34, who had lived at the
Morningside about 18 months. ``When I went out into the hallway I
did see smoke, so then I knew it was the real thing and not a false
alarm.''
   Ms. TeleRado said fire alarms were a frequent occurrence, and
said she initially ignored the warnings of a maintenance man who
pounded on hallway walls and yelled that there was a fire. An alarm
began ringing but stopped after about five minutes, she said. Other
residents, too, may have been slow to learn of the danger or respond
to warnings, she said.
   About 60 firefighters began a room-by-room search of the hotel
after the fire was extinguished, Taylor said. Two suffered minor
injuries.
   Many residents fled shoeless and in nightclothes, said the Rev.
Steven Newton, director of a newly opened homeless center who took
in 56 Morningside residents. Most depend on Social Security benefits
or other limited incomes and paid as little as $135 a month for
rooms, according to Newton and some residents.
   ``They were in the last kind of housing you can get before the
streets,'' said Newton. ``We're not talking about condominiums being
burned out.''
   Word of the fire brought an outpouring of food, clothing, gifts
and money to the homeless center. Showing a personal check made out
to the center for $1,000, center volunteer David T. Link said,
``Somebody just walked in off the street with that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
