<HEAD>IRA Car Bomb Hits Army Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA car bomb exploded in
Londonderry Sunday night and damaged 100 homes, including some
occupied by British soldiers and their families, police said.
   They said a 12-year-old boy and his mother, members of a civilian
family, were taken to a hospital and treated for shock. No other
injuries were reported.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army telephoned a 20-minute warning
about the bomb on a housing project in the city's Waterside
district, but it exploded after 15 minutes, police said.
   It was the fourth attack on British army homes in the province in
the past month.
   The IRA, fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite it with the Irish Republic, on Friday issued a one-week
deadline for the wives and children of British soldiers to get out
of what it called the ``war zone'' and return to the British
mainland.
   Some 10,500 British troops are currently deployed in Northern
Ireland. Unofficial estimates say between 1,500 and 2,000 soldiers
have their families with them.
   Since the IRA intensified attacks on British servicemen in March,
44 soldiers have been killed, including four at British bases in
continental Europe and one at a base in London.
