<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-Tents     12-18 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Tents,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aid Trip to Armenia To Build Plastic Tents Delayed Till Midweek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volunteers hoping to build durable plastic
tents for the earthquake victims in Armenia had another setback
Sunday when red tape problems kept them off a Soviet transport
plane, pushing back their scheduled departure three more days.
   Anthony Seraphin, president of Protect-A-Boat and Film
Applicators of North America, which came up with the idea for the
quick-to-build shelters, said his team now plans to leave from Miami
on Wednesday night on the first leg of a trip to the Soviet Union.
   The team also has been reduced from its originally planned 17
members after the Soviets gave permission for only 12 to enter,
Union Carbide Corp. spokesman John P. Yimoyines said. Carbide is
paying the estimated $100,000 cost of the effort and makes the resin
used in the plastic housing material.
   The crew will take 200,000 square feet of resin-based plastic
film and 24,000 feet of galvanized steel piping, enough to make 100
tents, Yimoyines said.
   The tents are constructed by building frames out of steel and
then shrink-wrapping plastic around them, using a propane heat gun.
Seraphin said it takes about two hours to build a tent that can
house 30 people and includes doors, windows and vents. The tents can
last two years.
   The team had hoped to board a Soviet IL-76 transport Sunday, but
the group could not get State Department approval for their trip in
time, the men said. Before that, the Air National Guard had offered
to transport the crew and their equipment if the Defense Department
would OK the flight, but the Pentagon said Friday it would have to
forward the request to the State Department for its approval this
week.
   ``I hope this one is for real,'' Yimoyines said of Wednesday's
planned flight. ``I think it is, because we even have flight numbers
this time.''
   The travel plans are being made by the Washington, D.C.-based
Armenian Relief Society, Seraphin said. A society spokesman, Greg
Beadian, said he would not release details of the plans until late
Monday after informing all the donors.
   Continental Airlines will fly the team and the tent-making
equipment from Newark, N.J., to Miami, Yimoyines said.
   The team intends to build five to 10 shelters in towns in the
quake area, where at least 55,000 were killed and 500,000 left
homeless by the Dec. 7 earthquake, Seraphin said.
   ``Then when we get back, we'll be raising money to send more
material over there so they can do it themselves,'' he said.
   The team will not return before Christmas, but Yimoyines said he
can't imagine a better place to be for the holiday.
   ``That's the reason we're all going,'' he said, adding that the
group was taking a small Christmas tree. ``It's mostly guys who see
a chance to help.''
</TEXT>
