<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Opposition,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Opposition Vows to Vote Out Sandinistas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people rallied Sunday to
mark the first anniversary of an opposition alliance, and they
listened to one leader pledge to beat the leftist government ``with
votes, not bullets.''
   The civic opposition now ``is more united, more cohesive and more
monolithic,'' Erick Ramirez of the Social Christian Party said at
the meeting Sunday. It will beat the Sandinistas in elections
scheduled for 1990 ``with votes, not bullets.''
   Hernaldo Zuniga of the Conservative Democratic Party said that
``Sandinista (government) efforts to divide the opposition'' have
failed. ``The Sandinista ideology and its political and economic
program are the biggest failure in the history of the country.''
   Police patrolled the area during the meeting of about 3,000
people. No violence was reported.
   The alliance is made up of 14 divergent groups, including Social
Christians, Liberals, Conservatives, Communists, Socialists, Social
Democrats, Central American Unionist parties, and the Workers
Permanent Congress. It was formed after a dialogue between the
government and opposition reached an impasse last December.
   The dialogue was initiated after Central American nations in
August 1987 signed regional accords that called for national peace
dialogues in the embattled region.
   The Sandinistas, who came to power through a revolution in 1979,
have been challenged by U.S.-backed rebels in an eight-year civil
war that has taken more than 50,000 lives. Most of the fighting
stopped when a cease-fire was declared in March.
   Mauricio Diaz, secretary general of the Popular Social Christian
Party, said that the Sandinista government increased its repression
in 1988, forcing thousands of Nicaraguans to flee to other countries.
</TEXT>
