<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Salomon III, one of the original owners
of the St. Louis Blues, died Sunday at his home in Tampa, Fla.,
following long bouts with cancer. He was 51.
   He and his father, insurance executives, paid $2 million to
establish the NHL expansion franchise in 1967, and it was ranked as
the best of six expansion teams of 1967-68, making the Stanley Cup
finals in its first three seasons.
   The Salomons sold the Blues in 1977 to Ralston Purina Corp. and
moved to Boca Raton, Fla. Sidney Salomon Jr. died in May 1986. Sid
Salomon III had been in the golf course business since moving to
Tampa several years ago.
