<DATELINE>DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pizza maker Celeste Lizio, whose
``Mama Celeste'' pizzas bore her name and her Italian cooking
skills, died Friday of complications from a heart ailment. She was
80.
   Mrs. Lizio created the brand that bears her name, and her
likeness appeared on millions of packages of ``Celeste'' pizza after
Chicago-based Quaker Oats food conglomerate acquired the product.
   She was born in San Angelo, Italy, in 1908 and emigrated to the
United States with her husband, the late Anthony Lizio, in the
1920s. The couple settled on Chicago's West Side and opened their
first restaurant in 1937.
   They closed that establishment in 1962 and then began selling
their pizzas to other restaurants.
