<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GoodGuys-Tower Bjt   12-18 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Good Guys-Tower, Bjt,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Retailers Launch One-Stop Entertainment Center Under Same Roof</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two retailers, leaders in different aspects
of the home entertainment industry, have joined forces to offer
consumers a rare one-stop music, video and electronics center under
the same roof.
   Good Guys Inc., sellers of hardware such as televisions and VCRs,
and Tower Records Inc., marketers of software like compact discs,
records and tapes, signed a lease linking both stores inside the
same building at the Stonestown Galleria.
   ``I've been retailing since I was 18 and I've never heard of two
retailers occupying the same lease,'' said Kevin McNeill, manager of
the Good Guys store at Stonestown. ``It's so logical. The software
and the hardware of our industry in one building _ it makes sense.''
   At the Stonestown Galleria, the innovation of the arrangement
becomes quickly obvious when shoppers view the stores' names printed
in bold red letters on separate sides of the old I. Magnin Building.
   Inside, Good Guys merchandise spreads across 18,000 square feet
on the first floor, while Tower Records takes up another 18,000
square feet on the second floor.
   The two stores are linked by escalator and elevator, and they
also share a freight elevator.
   ``It's working well for both of us so far,'' said Good Guys
President Ron Unkefer. The Good Guys store at Stonestown opened
three months prior to Tower Records' opening.
   The arrangement has also worked thus far for Tower, although it
will be about a year before the store's performance can be properly
evaluated, said Mike Sullivan, vice president.
   Sacramento-based Tower Records is a $380 million chain with 50
stores in the United States and eight overseas. The Good Guys is a
17-store, $150 million chain based in Burlingame.
   Tower Records opened its Stonestown store in late November, and
the Good Guys store manager said he noticed an immediate impact on
sales during the first weekend.
   ``I've seen an amazing change in the traffic pattern,'' said
McNeill, who's managed five Good Guys stores. ``We probably saw
double what we've been seeing _ and we've been here since August.''
   He said his salesmen advise customers who purchase hardware at
The Good Guys to go upstairs and buy the software at Tower Records
so they can immediately try out their product. He added that
customers are cross-shopping, or browsing from store to store.
   Linking the two stores resulted almost by accident, said Unkefer.
The Good Guys had located the prospective property, but the old I.
Magnin Building was too large to develop and the landlord only
wanted one entrance.
   Unkefer said he decided to proceed with the shared-leased plan
since the Good Guys and Tower Records already had a good
relationship _ they are neighbors in a number of communities and
Tower President Russ Solomon sits on the Good Guys board of
directors.
   A multimillion-dollar restoration of the building and about a
year of planning went into the project at Stonestown Galleria, a
sprawling shopping center on the southwestern corner of the city,
near San Francisco State University.
   Unkefer said there are no plans for similar ventures in the
future. ``But we're both viewing this as a test ... that we
certainly could do (again) in other cities and other markets.''
   In any case, Unkefer said customers can only benefit from such
shared-lease arrangements.
   ``Everything that's in the building is fun to buy. It's one-stop
shopping for home entertainment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
