<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1500EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TripleMileage     12-18 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Triple Mileage,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Ready to End Triple Mileage, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's major airlines are ready to end their
triple mileage programs _ but only if all the carriers do so,
according to some airline officials.
   The programs, in which airlines give frequent fliers three miles
of credit for each mile they fly, have been popular with the flying
public and costly for the major carriers.
   Delta Air Lines introduced triple mileage about a year ago, and
the others quickly followed suit.
   ``Triple miles truly sent a shock through the airline industry
and through American Airlines,'' Michael Gunn, American's senior
vice president of marketing, told The Dallas Morning News. ``It was
fundamentally unsound from an economic standpoint.''
   Delta's frequent flier membership increased by 2.5 million during
1988, and American's jumped by 1.5 million, The Morning News
reported in Sunday's editions.
   Last April, several carriers announced changes that effectively
pulled in the reins on free flying. And airlines could be ready now
to eliminate the triple mileage programs entirely, some experts say.
   ``Triple miles will pass into legend on Dec. 31st,'' Matt
Guilfoyle, Delta's director of consumer marketing, said last week.
   As Delta proved a year ago, only one airline has to break away
from the herd to start a stampede.
   ``There will be a move to slowly _ and I mean slowly _ tighten
the use of frequent flier mileage,'' said Paul Karos, an airline
analyst with First Boston Corp. ``But the airlines aren't going to
be able to get rid of the programs totally, nor would they want to.
They're a good marketing tool.''
   Analysts estimate that the potential cost of all frequent flier
miles _ when translated into free tickets and service upgrades _
could approach $1 billion. As much as half of that total is
attributable to triple mileage bonuses.
   At the same time, it appears increasingly likely that the
organization that sets accounting standards for U.S. businesses, the
American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, will soon
require airlines to list their potential frequent flier liabilities
on their balance sheets.
   In response, airlines are likely to find ways to remove the
mileage awards from their books, by putting an expiration date on
miles already earned or by putting a time limit on the use of future
mileage awards.
   Airlines also are increasing the use of ``blackout dates'' _
popular travel periods when tickets obtained as frequent flier
awards cannot be used _ and capacity control. With capacity control,
airlines limit the number of seats on each flight to be given away
to frequent fliers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881218-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1531EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspaperOutlook 1stLd-Writethru   12-18 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspaper Outlook, 1st Ld-Writethru,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Companies' Earnings Prospects Expected to Brighten in '89</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: restores dropped word `that' in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earnings outlook for the newspaper business
is expected to brighten next year despite what may be a shaky start
provided the economy avoids falling into a recession.
   That appeared to be the consensus among newspaper executives and
securities analysts who attended last week's PaineWebber Inc. media
conference.
   ``We are at the bottom of a trough right now and after a tough
first quarter, earnings should improve,'' said Edward Atorino, who
follows the media business for the investment firm Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co.
   Atorino said the newspaper companies should post earnings gains
from operations for all of 1989 that should average about 7 percent
to 8 percent compared with flat to lower performances in 1988.
   J. Kendrick Noble, the media analyst for PaineWebber and the
organizer of the 16th annual conference, said earnings may grow 10
percent next year mainly due to improved operating results.
   Noble said the major newspaper companies were able to post 10
percent earnings gains in 1988, but said most of the improvement was
due to the lower corporate tax rate while operating results were
steady.
   Knight Ridder Inc., Gannett Co. and New York Times Co., for
instance, each said they expected lower earnings in the first
quarter of 1989 but improvement for the rest of the year. Dow Jones
& Co. expects improved results at all of its operations next year
barring a recession, and Times-Mirror Co. said cost-containment
programs will help it post modest gains in 1989.
   Atorino said the main reason most newspaper companies expect a
tough first quarter is that the first three months of 1988 were
unusually strong.
   But the performance at most newspaper companies for the rest of
the year fell off sharply because of a decline in retail advertising
and increases in newsprint costs.
   The decline in retail advertising, a major contributor to most
newspapers' revenue, has been blamed on consolidation in the
retailing business, resistance to last spring's women's fashions and
possibly greater selectivity by consumers in a delayed response to
the October 1987 stock market crash.
   Atorino noted that newspaper profits were pressured by two
increases in 18 months in newsprint prices, which represents a
significant cost to publishers.
   He said the combination of lower ad revenue and higher newsprint
costs produced ``the most difficult year in 10 years'' for the
newspaper business.
   But Atorino and Noble said that after getting past the first
quarter, newspaper executives have good reason to be optimistic
about the year.
   Atorino said advertising revenue for newpapers should rise by
about 6 percent next year, up from about 4 percent in 1988.
   Noble expects classified advertising will grow at a slower pace
than this year, retail advertising should be about the same and
national advertising in newspapers should pick up after no growth
this year. He expects little change in overall ad revenue growth.
   But Noble said he expects a 6 percent increase in circulation
revenue, reflecting 1 percent real growth and rate hikes of about 5
percent.
   On the cost side, the analysts said newspapers should benefit
from cost-containment programs already in place, modest growth in
labor costs and smaller increases if any in newsprint prices.
   Noble said the industry has had to absorb newsprint price hikes
averaging 10 percent over the past two years but noted that there
are some doubts that the 4.5 percent hike posted by some major
producers for early 1989 will in fact take effect.
   Labor costs, on the other hand, should rise by a modest 3 percent
to 4 percent, Noble said.
   The net result, Atorino said, is that the combination of slightly
improved ad revenue, higher circulation revenue and slow growth in
labor and newsprint costs should lead to improving earnings.
   ``There is almost unanimous hope that business will be better in
'89,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
