<DOCNO> AP881218-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Iran-Oil     12-18 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Oil,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Finds Big New Oil, Gas Reserves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has discovered new oil fields with an
estimated 10 billion barrels, substantially boosting the country's
oil reserves, Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh announced Sunday.
   He said in an interview with Iran's state-run television,
monitored in Nicosia, that a major discovery was made at Koohe Mand
southeast of the northern Persian Gulf port of Bushehr.
   ``We have hit light and heavy crude (oil), and have discovered
substantial deposits of oil totalling 10 billion barrels,'' Aqazadeh
said.
   ``This is a new kind of discovery for our country, because we
have found very heavy crude of a kind which we did not have.''
   The oil discoveries will bolster Iran's efforts to finance its
reconstruction following the Aug. 20 cease-fire in its gulf war with
Iraq.
   The Koohe Mand discovery will increase Iran's current estimated
oil reserves of 93 billion barrels by more than 10 percent.
   Aqazadeh said that in addition to oil, a recent discovery of
``vast deposits of natural gas in Assaluyeh ... will boost our
natural gas reserves substantially.''
   The Iranian Oil Ministry disclosed in August that the gas find,
about 44 miles southeast of the big Kangan-Nar gas fields in the
central gulf, has a production capacity of 26 million cubic meters a
day.
   ``There might be further reserves deeper down,'' Aqazadeh noted.
   Iran's total gas reserves are estimated at more than 13 trillion
cubic meters.
   Aqazadeh said additional oil exploration projects were underway
in the Caspian Sea in northern Iran, as well as in the gulf. The
Iranians are likely to develop Caspian fields in cooperation with
the Soviet Union.
   He said ``work on the bottom of the Caspian Sea has also been
completed, and we hope to have a rig in place by next year in
cooperation with the Soviets. Soon after that, we hope to start our
drilling operations there.''
   Aqazadeh also referred to another recent oil find in Kheyrabad in
central Fars province, southeast of Shiraz.
   ``Preliminary exploration has put the capacity of the Kheyrabad
find at 200 million barrels of oil a day,'' he said. ``Due to the
high pressure of the deposits there, the first well should yield
about 400,000 barrels of oil a day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
