<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Debt     12-18 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Debt,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico to Cut Debt Payments by 50 Percent, Specialists Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico hopes to reduce payments on its foreign
debt by 50 percent in negotiations next year, the government
newspaper El Nacional on Sunday quoted private debt specialists as
saying.
   In its lead front-page story, the newspaper quoted the sources as
saying a 30 percent cut was feasible within a ``realistic term.''
The sources were not identified.
   They predicted that an agreement on reducing debt payments as of
1990 would be reached in the first two months of next year, the
newspaper said.
   Mexico's payments this year on its $102 billion foreign debt are
expected to total $14 billion.
   Last week, Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe said the country would
seek a reduction in debt service from the current level, the
equivalent of 5 percent of gross domestic product, to 3 percent of
GDP.
</TEXT>
