<FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BassGroup-Bank     12-18 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bass Group-Bank,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bass Group Names Antoci to Head American Savings and Loan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bass Group announced Sunday that Mario Antoci
will become chairman and chief executive officer of American Savings
and Loan before the year's end.
   Antoci, 54, now president and chief operating officer of H.F.
Ahmanson and Co., will assume the new post when the acquisition of
American Savings is completed by the Bass Group.
   ``Mario has demonstrated that a thrift can prosper in its
traditional role _ generating home mortgages with terms and pricing
that will meet consumer demands. His knowledge of the market and
reputation are excellent,'' Robert Bass said in an announcement.
   Antoci's experience includes a term with Home Savings and Loan,
an H.F. Ahmanson holding. Home Savings became the largest
home-mortgage lender in the thrift industry and the second-largest
resident mortgage lender nationally during Antoci's 21-year tenure.
   In a related announcement, Bass said William Popejoy, the current
chief executive officer of American Savings, will join an afiliate
of the Bass Group as a principal after working with Antoci in the
transition process. Popejoy will remain on the board of directors at
American Savings.
   ``The branch network (of American Savings) is solid, the
California industry is strong, and the thrift has an excellent
reputation for service,'' Antoci said. ``Most important, the Bass
commitment to the institution should provide confidence for
American's costumers and the financial strength to expand.''
   Antoci was named president and chief operating officer of Home
Savings in January 1984. In January 1987, he assumed the same
position with the parent company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
